{"title_page": "Environmental enrichment", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Behavioral enrichment}}\n[[File:Rat coming out cage.jpg|thumb|300px| A rodent is not stimulated by the environment in a wire cage, and this affects its brain negatively, particularly the complexity of its synaptic connections]]\n'''Environmental enrichment''' is the stimulation of the [[brain]] by its physical and social surroundings. Brains in richer, more stimulating environments have higher rates of [[synaptogenesis]] and more complex [[dendrites|dendrite arbors]], leading to increased brain activity. This effect takes place primarily during [[neurodevelopment]], but also during adulthood  to a lesser degree. With extra [[synapses]] there is also increased synapse activity, leading to an increased size and number of [[glia]]l energy-support cells. Environmental enrichment also enhances [[capillary]] vasculation, providing the neurons and glial cells with extra energy. The [[neuropil]] (neurons, glial cells, capillaries, combined together) expands, thickening the cortex. Research on rodent brains suggests that environmental enrichment may also lead to an increased rate of [[neurogenesis]].\n\nResearch on animals finds that environmental enrichment could aid the treatment and recovery of numerous brain-related dysfunctions, including [[Alzheimer's disease]] and those connected to [[aging]], whereas a lack of stimulation might impair cognitive development. Moreover, this research also suggests that environmental enrichment leads to a greater level of [[cognitive reserve]], the brain's resilience to the effects of conditions such as [[aging]] and [[dementia]].\n\nResearch on humans suggests that lack of stimulation delays and impairs cognitive development. Research also finds that attaining and engaging in higher levels of education, environments in which people participate in more challenging cognitively stimulating activities, results in greater cognitive reserve.\n\n== Early research ==\n[[Donald O. Hebb]] in 1947 found that rats raised as pets performed better on problem solving tests than rats raised in cages.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Hebb DO | title = The effects of early experience on problem solving at maturity | journal = American Psychologist | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = 306\u20137 | year = 1947 | doi = 10.1037/h0063667 }}</ref> His research, however, did not investigate the brain nor use standardized impoverished and enriched environments. Research doing this first was started in 1960 at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] by [[Mark Rosenzweig (psychologist)|Mark Rosenzweig]], who compared single rats in normal cages, and those placed in ones with toys, ladders, tunnels, running wheels in groups. This found that growing up in enriched environments affected enzyme [[cholinesterase]] activity.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1037/h0045402 |vauthors=Krech D, Rosenzweig MR, Bennett EL | title = Effects of environmental complexity and training on brain chemistry | journal = J Comp Physiol Psychol | volume = 53 | pages = 509\u201319 |date=December 1960 | pmid = 13754181 | issue = 6 }}</ref> This work led in 1962 to the discovery that environmental enrichment increased [[cerebral cortex]] volume.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1037/h0041137 |vauthors=Rosenzweig MR, Krech D, Bennett EL, Diamond MC | title = Effects of environmental complexity and training on brain chemistry and anatomy: a replication and extension | journal = J Comp Physiol Psychol | volume = 55 | pages = 429\u201337 |date=August 1962 | pmid = 14494091 | issue = 4 |url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/8h919150}}<!--http://www.escholarship.org/uc/item/8h919150 --></ref> In 1964, it was found that this was due to increased cerebral cortex thickness and greater [[synapse]] and [[glial]] numbers.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1038/2041161a0 |vauthors=Altman J, Das GD | title = Autoradiographic Examination of the Effects of Enriched Environment on the Rate of Glial Multiplication in the Adult Rat Brain | journal = Nature | volume = 204 | pages = 1161\u20133 |date=December 1964 | pmid = 14264369 | issue = 4964 }}</ref><ref name=\"DiamondKrech\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1002/cne.901230110 |vauthors=Diamond MC, Krech D, Rosenzweig MR | title = The Effects of an Enriched Environment on the Histology of the Rat Cerebral Cortex | journal = J. Comp. Neurol. | volume = 123 | pages = 111\u201320 |date=August 1964 | pmid = 14199261 }}</ref>\n\nAlso starting around 1960, [[Harry Harlow]] studied the effects of [[maternal deprivation|maternal and social deprivation]] on [[rhesus monkey]] infants (a form of environmental stimulus deprivation). This established the importance of social stimulation for normal [[cognitive development|cognitive]] and emotional development.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Harlow HF, Rowland GL, Griffin GA | title = The Effect of Total Social Deprivation on the Development of Monkey Behavior | journal = Psychiatr Res Rep Am Psychiatr Assoc | volume = 19 | pages = 116\u201335 |date=December 1964 | pmid = 14232649 }}</ref>\n\n== Synapses ==\n\n=== Synaptogenesis ===\n\nRats raised with environmental enrichment have thicker cerebral cortices (3.3\u20137%) that contain 25% more [[synapses]].<ref name=\"DiamondKrech\" /><ref name=\"DiamondLaw\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Diamond MC, Law F, Rhodes H | title = Increases in cortical depth and glia numbers in rats subjected to enriched environment | journal = J. Comp. Neurol. | volume = 128 | issue = 1 | pages = 117\u201326 |date=September 1966 | pmid = 4165855 | doi = 10.1002/cne.901280110 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> This effect of environmental richness upon the brain occurs whether it is experienced immediately following birth,<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.167.3916.292 |vauthors=Schapiro S, Vukovich KR | title = Early experience effects upon cortical dendrites: a proposed model for development | journal = Science | volume = 167 | issue = 3916 | pages = 292\u20134 |date=January 1970 | pmid = 4188192 }}</ref> after weaning,<ref name=\"DiamondKrech\" /><ref name=\"DiamondLaw\" /><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Bennett EL, Diamond MC, Krech D, Rosenzweig MR | title = Chemical and Anatomical Plasticity Brain | journal = Science | volume = 146 | pages = 610\u20139 |date=October 1964 | pmid = 14191699 | doi = 10.1126/science.146.3644.610 | issue = 3644 }}</ref> or during maturity.<ref name=\"Briones\" >{{cite journal |vauthors=Briones TL, Klintsova AY, Greenough WT | title = Stability of synaptic plasticity in the adult rat visual cortex induced by complex environment exposure | journal = Brain Res. | volume = 1018 | issue = 1 | pages = 130\u20135 |date=August 2004 | pmid = 15262214 | doi = 10.1016/j.brainres.2004.06.001 }}</ref> When synapse numbers increase in adults, they can remain high in number even when the adults are returned to impoverished environment for 30 days<ref name=\"Briones\" /> suggesting that such increases in synapse numbers are not necessarily temporary. However, the increase in synapse numbers has been observed generally to reduce with maturation.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Holtmaat AJ, Trachtenberg JT, Wilbrecht L | title = Transient and persistent dendritic spines in the neocortex in vivo | journal = Neuron | volume = 45 | issue = 2 | pages = 279\u201391 |date=January 2005 | pmid = 15664179 | doi = 10.1016/j.neuron.2005.01.003 |display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Zuo Y, Lin A, Chang P, Gan WB | title = Development of long-term dendritic brain stability in diverse regions of cerebral cortex | journal = Neuron | volume = 46 | issue = 2 | pages = 181\u20139 |date=April 2005 | pmid = 15848798 | doi = 10.1016/j.neuron.2005.04.001 }}</ref> Stimulation affects not only synapses upon [[pyramidal neuron]]s (the main projecting neurons in the cerebral cortex) but also [[stellate cell|stellate]] ones (that are usually [[interneurons]]).<ref name=\"Greenough\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0014-4886(73)90090-3 |vauthors=Greenough WT, Volkmar FR | title = Pattern of dendritic branching in occipital cortex of rats reared in complex environments | journal = Exp. Neurol. | volume = 40 | issue = 2 | pages = 491\u2013504 |date=August 1973 | pmid = 4730268 }}</ref> It can also affect neurons outside the brain, such as those in the [[retina]].<ref name=\"Landi, S. 2007\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Landi S, Sale A, Berardi N, Viegi A, Maffei L, Cenni MC | title = Retinal functional development is sensitive to environmental enrichment: a role for BDNF | journal = FASEB J. | volume = 21 | issue = 1 | pages = 130\u20139 |date=January 2007 | pmid = 17135370 | doi = 10.1096/fj.06-6083com | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c5897cdbaa09aec195892d6740faa002aea460f8 }}</ref>\n\n=== Dendrite complexity ===\nEnvironmental enrichment affects the complexity and length of the [[dendrite]] arbors (upon which synapses form). Higher-order dendrite branch complexity is increased in enriched environments,<ref name=\"Greenough\" /><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.176.4042.1445 |vauthors=Volkmar FR, Greenough WT | title = Rearing complexity affects branching of dendrites in the visual cortex of the rat | journal = Science | volume = 176 | issue = 4042 | pages = 1445\u20137 |date=June 1972 | pmid = 5033647 }}</ref> as can the length, in young animals, of distal branches.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0163-1047(92)90937-Y |vauthors=Wallace CS, Kilman VL, Withers GS, Greenough WT | title = Increases in dendritic length in occipital cortex after 4 days of differential housing in weanling rats | journal = Behav. Neural Biol. | volume = 58 | issue = 1 | pages = 64\u20138 |date=July 1992 | pmid = 1417672 }}</ref>\n\n=== Activity and energy consumption ===\nAnimals in enriched environments show evidence of increased synapse activation.<ref name=\"Sirevaag\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Sirevaag AM, Greenough WT | title = Differential rearing effects on rat visual cortex synapses. III. Neuronal and glial nuclei, boutons, dendrites, and capillaries | journal = Brain Res. | volume = 424 | issue = 2 | pages = 320\u201332 |date=October 1987 | pmid = 3676831 | doi = 10.1016/0006-8993(87)91477-6}}</ref> Synapses tend to also be much larger.<ref name=\"sievaag85\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Sirevaag AM, Greenough WT | title = Differential rearing effects on rat visual cortex synapses. II. Synaptic morphometry | journal = Brain Res. | volume = 351 | issue = 2 | pages = 215\u201326 |date=April 1985 | pmid = 3995348 | doi = 10.1016/0165-3806(85)90193-2}}</ref> [[Gamma wave|Gamma oscillations]] become larger in amplitude in the hippocampus.<ref name=\"Shinohara\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1038/ncomms2658 |vauthors=Shinohara Y, Hosoya A, Hirase H | title = Experience enhances gamma oscillations and interhemispheric asymmetry in the hippocampus | journal = Nat Commun | volume = 4 | pages = 1652 |date=April 2013 | pmid = 23552067 | issue=4 | pmc=3644069}}</ref> This increased energy consumption is reflected in glial and local capillary vasculation that provides synapses with extra energy.\n* Glial cell numbers per neuron increase 12\u201314%<ref name=\"DiamondKrech\" /><ref name=\"DiamondLaw\" />\n* The direct apposition area of glial cells with synapses expands by 19%<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Jones TA, Greenough WT | title = Ultrastructural evidence for increased contact between astrocytes and synapses in rats reared in a complex environment | journal = Neurobiol Learn Mem | volume = 65 | issue = 1 | pages = 48\u201356 |date=January 1996 | pmid = 8673406 | doi = 10.1006/nlme.1996.0005 }}</ref>\n* The volume of glial cell nuclei for each synapse is higher by 37.5%<ref name=\"Sirevaag\" />\n* The mean volume of mitochondria per neuron is 20% greater<ref name=\"Sirevaag\" />\n* The volume of glial cell nuclei for each neuron is 63% higher<ref name=\"Sirevaag\" />\n* Capillary density is increased.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Borowsky IW, Collins RC | title = Metabolic anatomy of brain: a comparison of regional capillary density, glucose metabolism, and enzyme activities | journal = J. Comp. Neurol. | volume = 288 | issue = 3 | pages = 401\u201313 |date=October 1989 | pmid = 2551935 | doi = 10.1002/cne.902880304 }}</ref>\n* Capillaries are wider (4.35 \u03bcm compared to 4.15 \u03bcm in controls)<ref name=\"Sirevaag\" />\n* Shorter distance exist between any part of the [[neuropil]] and a capillary (27.6 \u03bcm compared to 34.6 \u03bcm)<ref name=\"Sirevaag\" />\nThese energy related changes to the [[neuropil]] are responsible for increasing the volume of the cerebral cortex (the increase in synapse numbers contributes in itself hardly any extra volume).\n\n=== Motor learning stimulation ===\nPart of the effect of environmental enrichment is providing opportunities to acquire [[motor skills]]. Research on rats learning an \u201cacrobatic\u201d skill shows that such learning activity leads to increased synapse count.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1073/pnas.87.14.5568 |vauthors=Black JE, Isaacs KR, Anderson BJ, Alcantara AA, Greenough WT | title = Learning causes synaptogenesis, whereas motor activity causes angiogenesis, in cerebellar cortex of adult rats | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 87 | issue = 14 | pages = 5568\u201372 |date=July 1990 | pmid = 1695380 | pmc = 54366 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kleim JA, Hogg TM, VandenBerg PM, Cooper NR, Bruneau R, Remple M | title = Cortical synaptogenesis and motor map reorganization occur during late, but not early, phase of motor skill learning | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 24 | issue = 3 | pages = 628\u201333 |date=January 2004 | pmid = 14736848 | pmc = 6729261 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.3440-03.2004 }}</ref>\n\n=== Maternal transmission ===\nEnvironmental enrichment during [[pregnancy]] has effects upon the [[fetus]], such as accelerating his or her retinal development.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Sale A, Cenni MC, Ciucci F, Putignano E, Chierzi S, Maffei L| title = Maternal Enrichment during Pregnancy Accelerates Retinal Development of the Fetus | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 2 | issue = 11 | pages = e1160 | year = 2007 | pmid = 18000533 | pmc = 2063464 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0001160 | editor1-last = Reh | editor1-first = Thomas }} {{open access}}</ref>\n\n== Neurogenesis ==\nEnvironmental enrichment can also lead to the [[neurogenesis|formation of neurons]] (at least in rats)<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Fan Y, Liu Z, Weinstein PR, Fike JR, Liu J | title = Environmental enrichment enhances neurogenesis and improves functional outcome after cranial irradiation | journal = Eur. J. Neurosci. | volume = 25 | issue = 1 | pages = 38\u201346 |date=January 2007 | pmid = 17241265 | doi = 10.1111/j.1460-9568.2006.05269.x }}</ref> and reverse both the loss of neurons in the [[hippocampus]] and memory impairment from chronic stress.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Veena J, Srikumar BN, Mahati K, Bhagya V, Raju TR, Shankaranarayana Rao BS | title = Enriched environment restores hippocampal cell proliferation and ameliorates cognitive deficits in chronically stressed rats | journal = J. Neurosci. Res. | volume = 87 | issue = 4 | pages = 831\u201343 |date=March 2009 | pmid = 19006089 | doi = 10.1002/jnr.21907 }}</ref> However, its relevance has been questioned for the behavioral effects of enriched environments.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Meshi D, Drew MR, Saxe M | title = Hippocampal neurogenesis is not required for behavioral effects of environmental enrichment | journal = Nat. Neurosci. | volume = 9 | issue = 6 | pages = 729\u201331 |date=June 2006 | pmid = 16648847 | doi = 10.1038/nn1696 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n== Mechanisms ==\n\nEnriched environments affect the expression of [[genes]] that determine neuronal structure in the cerebral cortex and hippocampus.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Rampon C, Jiang CH, Dong H | title = Effects of environmental enrichment on gene expression in the brain | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 97 | issue = 23 | pages = 12880\u20134 |date=November 2000 | pmid = 11070096 | pmc = 18858 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.97.23.12880 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> At the molecular level, this occurs through increased concentrations of the [[neurotrophins]] [[Nerve growth factor|NGF]], [[NT-3]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ickes BR, Pham TM, Sanders LA, Albeck DS, Mohammed AH, Granholm AC | title = Long-term environmental enrichment leads to regional increases in neurotrophin levels in rat brain | journal = Exp. Neurol. | volume = 164 | issue = 1 | pages = 45\u201352 |date=July 2000 | pmid = 10877914 | doi = 10.1006/exnr.2000.7415 }}</ref><ref name=\"Torasdotter, M. 1998\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0166-4328(97)00142-3 |vauthors=Torasdotter M, Metsis M, Henriksson BG, Winblad B, Mohammed AH | title = Environmental enrichment results in higher levels of nerve growth factor mRNA in the rat visual cortex and hippocampus | journal = Behav. Brain Res. | volume = 93 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 83\u201390 |date=June 1998 | pmid = 9659990 }}</ref> and changes in [[BDNF]].<ref name=\"Landi, S. 2007\" /><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Zhu SW, Codita A, Bogdanovic N | title = Influence of environmental manipulation on exploratory behaviour in male BDNF knockout mice | journal = Behav. Brain Res. | volume = 197 | issue = 2 | pages = 339\u201346 |date=February 2009 | pmid = 18951926 | doi = 10.1016/j.bbr.2008.09.032 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> This alters the activation of [[cholinergic]] neurons,<ref name=\"Torasdotter, M. 1998\" /> [[5-HT]],<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0169-328X(97)00317-3 |vauthors=Rasmuson S, Olsson T, Henriksson BG | title = Environmental enrichment selectively increases 5-HT1A receptor mRNA expression and binding in the rat hippocampus | journal = Brain Res. Mol. Brain Res. | volume = 53 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 285\u201390 |date=January 1998 | pmid = 9473697 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> and [[Adrenergic receptor|beta-adrenolin]].<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1006/nlme.1995.1043 |vauthors=Escorihuela RM, Fern\u00e1ndez-Teruel A, Tobe\u00f1a A | title = Early environmental stimulation produces long-lasting changes on beta-adrenoceptor transduction system | journal = Neurobiol Learn Mem | volume = 64 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201357 |date=July 1995 | pmid = 7582812 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> Another effect is to increase proteins such as [[synaptophysin]] and [[DLG4|PSD-95]] in synapses.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Nithianantharajah J, Levis H, Murphy M | title = Environmental enrichment results in cortical and subcortical changes in levels of synaptophysin and PSD-95 proteins | journal = Neurobiol Learn Mem | volume = 81 | issue = 3 | pages = 200\u201310 |date=May 2004 | pmid = 15082021 | doi = 10.1016/j.nlm.2004.02.002 }}</ref> Changes in [[Wnt signaling pathway|Wnt signaling]] have also been found to mimic in adult mice the effects of environmental enrichment upon synapses in the hippocampus.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Gogolla N, Galimberti I, Deguchi Y, Caroni P | title = Wnt signaling mediates experience-related regulation of synapse numbers and mossy fiber connectivities in the adult hippocampus | journal = Neuron | volume = 62 | issue = 4 | pages = 510\u201325 |date=May 2009 | pmid = 19477153 | doi = 10.1016/j.neuron.2009.04.022 }}</ref> Increase in neurons numbers could be linked to changes in [[Vascular endothelial growth factor|VEGF]].<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.2174/156720506775697133 | vauthors = During MJ, Cao L | title = VEGF, a mediator of the effect of experience on hippocampal neurogenesis | journal = Curr Alzheimer Res | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | pages = 29\u201333 | date = February 2006 | pmid = 16472200 | url = http://www.bentham-direct.org/pages/content.php?CAR/2006/00000003/00000001/007AT.SGM | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120722155514/http://www.bentham-direct.org/pages/content.php?CAR/2006/00000003/00000001/007AT.SGM | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2012-07-22 }}</ref>\n\n== Rehabilitation and resilience ==\n\nResearch in animals suggests that environmental enrichment aids  recovery from certain neurological disorders and cognitive impairments. There are two mains areas of focus: neurological rehabilitation and [[cognitive reserve]], the brain's resistance to the effects of exposure to physical, natural, and social threats. Although most of these experiments used animal subjects, mainly rodents, researchers have pointed to the affected areas of animal brains to which human brains are most similar and used their findings as evidence to show that humans would have comparable reactions to enriched environments. The tests done on animals are thus meant to represent human simulations for the following list of conditions.\n\n===Neurological rehabilitation===\n\n====Autism====\n\nA study conducted in 2011 led to the conclusion that environmental enrichment vastly improves the cognitive ability of children with [[autism]]. The study found that autistic children who receive [[olfactory stimulation|olfactory]] and [[tactile stimulation]] along with [[exercises]] that stimulated other paired sensory modalities clinically improved by 42 percent while autistic children not receiving this treatment clinically improved by just 7 percent.<ref name = Woo>{{cite journal |vauthors=Woo CC, Leon M |title=Environmental Enrichment as an Effective Treatment for Autism: A Randomized Controlled Trial |journal=Behav Neurosci |volume=127 |issue=4 |pages=487\u201397 |date=March 2011 |pmid=23688137 |doi=10.1037/a0033010 |url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/5zf6s24x }}</ref> The same study also showed that there was significant clinical improvement in autistic children exposed to enriched sensorimotor environments, and a vast majority of parents reported that their child's quality of life was much better with the treatment.<ref name = Woo/>  A second study confirmed its effectiveness.  The second study also found after 6 months of sensory enrichment therapy, 21% of the children who initially had been given an autism classification, using the Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule, improved to the point that, although they remained on the autism spectrum, they no longer met the criteria for classic autism. None of the standard care controls reached an equivalent level of improvement.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Woo, Cynthia C. |author2=Donnelly, Joseph H. |author3=Steinberg-Epstein, Robin |author4=Leon, Michael | title=Environmental enrichment as a therapy for autism: A clinical trial replication and extension |journal=Behavioral Neuroscience |pages= 412\u2013422|date=Aug 2015 |pmid= 26052790|doi=10.1037/bne0000068 |volume=129 |issue=4 |pmc=4682896}}</ref> The therapy using the methodologies is titled [[Sensory Enrichment Therapy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.webmd.com/brain/autism/news/20130605/sensory-focused-autism-therapy-shows-early-promise |title='Sensory-Focused' Autism Therapy Shows Early Promise |author=Mary Brophy Marcus |date=June 5, 2013 |website=webmd.com |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ksl.com/?sid=31896222&nid=148&title=autism-treatment-gives-utah-family-hope |title=Autism treatment gives Utah family hope |author=Nkoyo Iyamba |date=October 9, 2014 |website=ksl.com |publisher= |access-date= |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925105355/https://www.ksl.com/?sid=31896222&nid=148&title=autism-treatment-gives-utah-family-hope |archive-date=September 25, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Alzheimer's disease====\n\nThrough environmental enrichment, researchers were able to enhance and partially repair memory deficits in mice between ages of 2 to 7 months with characteristics of [[Alzheimer's disease]]. Mice in enriched environments performed significantly better on object recognition tests and the [[Morris water navigation task|Morris Water Maze]] than they had when they were in standard environments. It was thus concluded that environmental enrichment enhances visual and learning memory for those with Alzheimer's.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Berardi N, Braschi C, Capsoni S, Cattaneo A, Maffei L |title=Environmental enrichment delays the onset of memory deficits and reduces neuropathological hallmarks in a mouse model of Alzheimer-like neurodegeneration |journal=J. Alzheimers Dis. |volume=11 |issue=3 |pages=359\u201370 |date=June 2007 |pmid=17851186 |url=http://iospress.metapress.com/openurl.asp?genre=article&issn=1387-2877&volume=11&issue=3&spage=359 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120720095948/http://iospress.metapress.com/openurl.asp?genre=article&issn=1387-2877&volume=11&issue=3&spage=359 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-20 |doi=10.3233/JAD-2007-11312 }}</ref> Furthermore, it has been found that mouse models of Alzheimer's disease that were exposed to enriched environment before amyloid onset (at 3 months of age) and then returned to their home cage for over 7 months, showed preserved spatial memory and reduced amyloid deposition at 13 months old, when they are supposed to show dramatic memory deficits and amyloid plaque load. These findings reveal the preventive, and long-lasting effects of early life stimulating experience on Alzheimer-like pathology in mice and likely reflect the capacity of enriched environment to efficiently stimulate the [[cognitive reserve]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Verret L, Krezymon A, Halley H, Trouche S, Zerwas M, Lazouret M, Lassalle JM, Rampon C | title = Transient enriched housing before amyloidosis onset sustains cognitive improvement in Tg2576 mice | journal = Neurobiology of Aging | volume = 34 | issue = 1 | pages = 211\u201325 |date=Jan 2013 | pmid = 22727275 | doi=10.1016/j.neurobiolaging.2012.05.013}}</ref>\n\n====Huntington's disease====\n\nResearch has indicated that environmental enrichment can help relieve motor and psychiatric deficits caused by [[Huntington's disease]]. It also improves lost protein levels for those with the disease, and prevents striatal and hippocampal deficits in the [[BDNF]], located in the hippocampus.<ref name = Spires>{{cite journal |vauthors=Spires TL, Grote HE, Varshney NK | title = Environmental enrichment rescues protein deficits in a mouse model of Huntington's disease, indicating a possible disease mechanism | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 24 | issue = 9 | pages = 2270\u20136 |date=March 2004 | pmid = 14999077 | pmc = 6730435 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.1658-03.2004 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> These findings have led researchers to suggest that environmental enrichment has a potential to be a possible form of therapy for those with Huntington's.<ref name = Spires/>\n\n====Parkinson's disease====\n\nMultiple studies have reported that environmental enrichment for adult mice helps relieve neuronal death, which is particularly beneficial to those with [[Parkinson's disease]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Faherty CJ, Raviie Shepherd K, Herasimtschuk A, Smeyne RJ | title = Environmental enrichment in adulthood eliminates neuronal death in experimental Parkinsonism | journal = Brain Res. Mol. Brain Res. | volume = 134 | issue = 1 | pages = 170\u20139 |date=March 2005 | pmid = 15790541 | doi = 10.1016/j.molbrainres.2004.08.008 }}</ref> A more recent study shows that environmental enrichment particularly affects the [[nigrostriatal pathway]], which is important for managing [[dopamine]] and acetylcholine levels, critical for motor deficits.<ref name = Goldberg>{{cite journal|last=Goldberg|first=NR|author2=Fields, V |author3=Pflibsen, L |author4=Salvatore, MF |author5= Meshul, CK |title=Social enrichment attenuates nigrostriatal lesioning and reverses motor impairment in a progressive 1-methyl-2-phenyl-1,2,3,6-tetrahydropyridine (MPTP) mouse model of Parkinson's disease.|journal=Neurobiology of Disease|date=March 2012|volume=45|issue=3|pages=1051\u201367|pmid=22198503|doi=10.1016/j.nbd.2011.12.024}}</ref>  Moreover, it was found that environmental enrichment has beneficial effects for the social implications of Parkinson's disease.<ref name = Goldberg/>\n\n====Stroke====\n\nResearch done in animals has shown that subjects recovering in an enriched environment 15 days after having a [[stroke]] had significantly improved neurobehavioral function. In addition these same subjects showed greater capability of learning and larger infarct post-intervention than those who were not in an enriched environment. It was thus concluded that environmental enrichment had a considerable beneficial effect on the learning and sensorimotor functions on animals post-stroke.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Janssen H, Bernhardt J, Collier JM, Sena ES, McElduff P, Attia J, Pollack M, Howells DW, Nilsson M, Calford MB, Spratt NJ |title=An Enriched Environment Improves Sensorimotor Function Post-Ischemic Stroke|journal=Neurorehabilitation and Neural Repair|date=12 September 2010|volume=24|issue=9|pages=802\u2013813|doi=10.1177/1545968310372092|pmid=20834046|url=https://www.pure.ed.ac.uk/ws/files/8123036/Janssen_et_al_2010.pdf}}<!--https://www.pure.ed.ac.uk/ws/files/8123036/Janssen_et_al_2010.pdf--></ref> A 2013 study also found that environmental enrichment socially benefits patients recovering from stroke. Researchers in that study concluded that stroke patients in enriched environments in assisted-care facilities are much more likely to be engaging with other patients during normal social hours instead of being alone or sleeping.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Janssen|first=Heidi|author2=Ada, Louise |author3=Bernhardt, Julie |author4=McElduff, Patrick |author5=Pollack, Michael |author6=Nilsson, Michael |author7= Spratt, Neil J. |title=An enriched environment increases activity in stroke patients undergoing rehabilitation in a mixed rehabilitation unit: a pilot non-randomized controlled trial|journal=Disability and Rehabilitation|date=29 April 2013|pages=255\u2013262|doi=10.3109/09638288.2013.788218|pmid=23627534 |volume=36 |issue=3}}</ref>\n\n====Rett syndrome====\n\nA 2008 study found that environmental enrichment was significant in aiding recovery of motor coordination and some recovery of BDNF levels in female mice with conditions similar to those of [[Rett syndrome]]. Over the course of 30 weeks female mice in enriched environments showed superior ability in motor coordination to those in standard conditions.<ref name = Kondo>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kondo M, Gray LJ, Pelka GJ, Christodoulou J, Tam PP, Hannan AJ | title = Environmental enrichment ameliorates a motor coordination deficit in a mouse model of Rett syndrome--Mecp2 gene dosage effects and BDNF expression | journal = Eur. J. Neurosci. | volume = 27 | issue = 12 | pages = 3342\u201350 |date=June 2008 | pmid = 18557922 | doi = 10.1111/j.1460-9568.2008.06305.x }}</ref> Although they were unable to have full motor capability, they were able to prevent a more severe motor deficit by living in an enriched environment. These results combined with increased levels of BDNF in the cerebellum led researchers to conclude that an enriched environment that stimulates areas of the motor cortex and areas of the cerebellum having to do with motor learning is beneficial in aiding mice with Rett syndrome.<ref name = Kondo/>\n\n====Amblyopia====\n\nA recent study found that adult rats with [[amblyopia]] improved visual acuity two weeks after being placed into an enriched environment.<ref name = Sale>{{cite journal |vauthors=Sale A, Maya Vetencourt JF, Medini P | title = Environmental enrichment in adulthood promotes amblyopia recovery through a reduction of intracortical inhibition | journal = Nat. Neurosci. | volume = 10 | issue = 6 | pages = 679\u201381 |date=June 2007 | pmid = 17468749 | doi = 10.1038/nn1899 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> The same study showed that another two weeks after ending environmental enrichment, the rats retained their visual acuity improvement. Conversely, rats in a standard environment showed no improvement in visual acuity. It was thus concluded that environmental enrichment reduces GABA inhibition and increases BDNF expression in the visual cortex. As a result, the growth and development of neurons and synapses in the visual cortex were much improved due to the enriched environment.<ref name = Sale/>\n\n====Sensory deprivation====\n\nStudies have shown that with the help of environmental enrichment the effects of [[sensory deprivation]] can be corrected. For example, a visual impairment known as \"dark-rearing\" in the visual cortex can be prevented and rehabilitated. In general, an enriched environment will  improve, if not repair, the sensory systems animals possess.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7580.2009.01103.x |vauthors=Argando\u00f1a EG, Bengoetxea H, Lafuente JV | title = Physical exercise is required for environmental enrichment to offset the quantitative effects of dark-rearing on the S-100\u03b2 astrocytic density in the rat visual cortex | journal = Journal of Anatomy | volume = 215 | issue = 2 | pages = 132\u2013140 | year = 2009 | pmid = 19500177 | pmc = 2740960 }}</ref>\n\n====Lead poisoning====\n\nDuring development, [[gestation]] is one of the most critical periods for exposure to any lead. Exposure to high levels of lead at this time can lead to inferior spatial learning performance. Studies have shown that environmental enrichment can overturn damage to the hippocampus induced by [[lead poisoning|lead exposure]].<ref name = Cao>{{cite journal|last=Cao|first=Xiujing|author2=Huang, Shenghai |author3=Ruan, Diyun |title=Enriched environment restores impaired hippocampal long-term potentiation and water maze performance induced by developmental lead exposure in rats|journal=Developmental Psychobiology|date=April 2008|volume=50|issue=3|pages=307\u2013313|doi=10.1002/dev.20287|pmid=18335502}}</ref>  Learning and spatial memory that are dependent on the long-term potentiation of the hippocampus are vastly improve as subjects in an enriched environments had lower levels of lead concentration in their hippocampi. The findings also showed that enriched environments result in some natural protection of lead-induced brain deficits.<ref name = Cao/>\n\n====Chronic spinal cord injuries====\n\nResearch has indicated that animals suffering from [[spinal cord injuries]] showed significant improvement in motor capabilities even with a long delay in treatment after the injury when exposed to environmental enrichment.<ref name = Fischer>{{cite journal |vauthors=Fischer FR, Peduzzi JD | title = Functional Recovery in Rats With Chronic Spinal Cord Injuries After Exposure to an Enriched Environment | journal = J Spinal Cord Med | volume = 30 | issue = 2 | pages = 147\u201355 | year = 2007 | pmid = 17591227 | pmc = 2031947 | doi = 10.1080/10790268.2007.11753926 }}</ref> Social interactions, exercise, and novelty all play major roles in aiding the recovery of an injured subject. This has led to some suggestions that the spinal cord has a continued plasticity and all efforts must be made for enriched environments to stimulate this plasticity in order to aid recovery.<ref name = Fischer/>\n\n====Maternal deprivation stress====\n\n[[Maternal deprivation]] can be caused by the abandonment by a nurturing parent at a young age. In rodents or nonhuman primates, this leads to a higher vulnerability for\nstress-related illness.<ref name = Francis>{{cite journal |vauthors=Francis DD, Diorio J, Plotsky PM, Meaney MJ | title = Environmental enrichment reverses the effects of maternal separation on stress reactivity | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 22 | issue = 18 | pages = 7840\u20133 |date=September 2002 | pmid = 12223535 | pmc = 6758090 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.22-18-07840.2002 }}</ref> Research suggests that environmental enrichment can reverse the effects of maternal separation on stress reactivity, possibly by affecting the hippocampus and the prefrontal cortex.<ref name = Francis/>\n\n====Child neglect====\n\nIn all children, maternal care is one of the significant influences for hippocampal development, providing the foundation for stable and individualized learning and memory. However, this is not the case for those who have experienced [[child neglect]]. Researchers determined that through environmental enrichment, a neglected child can partially receive the same hippocampal development and stability, albeit not at the same level as that of the presence of a parent or guardian.<ref name = Bredy>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0306-4522(02)00918-1 |vauthors=Bredy TW, Humpartzoomian RA, Cain DP, Meaney MJ | title = Partial reversal of the effect of maternal care on cognitive function through environmental enrichment | journal = Neuroscience | volume = 118 | issue = 2 | pages = 571\u20136 | year = 2003 | pmid = 12699791 }}</ref> The results were comparable to those of child intervention programs, rendering environmental enrichment a useful method for dealing with child neglect.<ref name = Bredy/>{{failed verification|I do not have access to full article, but it describes a study with rats, in which the effects of being raised by mothers with low licking/grooming behavior were reversed through environmental enrichment at the behavioral level but not at the physiological level.|date=January 2014}}\n\n=== Cognitive reserve ===\n\n====Aging====\n\nDecreased hippocampal neurogenesis is a characteristic of [[aging]]. Environmental enrichment increases neurogenesis in aged rodents by potentiating neuronal differentiation and new cell survival.<ref name = Kumar>{{cite journal|last=Speisman|first=RB|author2=Kumar, A |author3=Rani, A |author4=Pastoriza, JM |author5=Severance, JE |author6=Foster, TC |author7= Ormerod, BK |title=Environmental enrichment restores neurogenesis and rapid acquisition in aged rats.|journal=Neurobiology of Aging|date=January 2013|volume=34|issue=1|pages=263\u201374|pmid=22795793|doi=10.1016/j.neurobiolaging.2012.05.023 |pmc=3480541}}</ref> As a result, subjects exposed to environmental enrichment aged better due to superior ability in retaining their levels of spatial and learning memory.<ref name = Kumar/>\n\n====Prenatal and perinatal cocaine exposure====\n\nResearch has shown that mice exposed to environmental enrichment are less affected by the consequences of [[Cocaine#Effects in pregnancy and nursing|cocaine exposure]] in comparison with those in standard environments. Although the levels of dopamine in the brains of both sets of mice were relatively similar, when both subjects were exposed to the cocaine injection, mice in enriched environment were significantly less responsive than those in standard environments.<ref name = Solinas>{{cite journal |vauthors=Solinas M, Thiriet N, El Rawas R, Lardeux V, Jaber M | title = Environmental enrichment during early stages of life reduces the behavioral, neurochemical, and molecular effects of cocaine | journal = Neuropsychopharmacology | volume = 34 | issue = 5 | pages = 1102\u201311 |date=April 2009 | pmid = 18463628 | doi = 10.1038/npp.2008.51 }}</ref> It was thus concluded that both the activating and rewarding effects are suppressed by environmental enrichment and early exposure to environmental enrichment can help prevent [[drug addiction]].<ref name = Solinas/>\n\n== Humans ==\n\nThough environmental enrichment research has been mostly done upon rodents, similar effects occur in primates,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kozorovitskiy Y, Gross CG, Kopil C | title = Experience induces structural and biochemical changes in the adult primate brain | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 102 | issue = 48 | pages = 17478\u201382 |date=November 2005 | pmid = 16299105 | pmc = 1297690 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0508817102 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> and are likely to affect the human brain. However, direct research upon human synapses and their numbers is limited since this requires [[histological]] study of the brain. A link, however, has been found between educational level and greater dendritic branch complexity following autopsy removal of the brain.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Jacobs B, Schall M, Scheibel AB | title = A quantitative dendritic analysis of Wernicke's area in humans. II. Gender, hemispheric, and environmental factors | journal = J. Comp. Neurol. | volume = 327 | issue = 1 | pages = 97\u2013111 |date=January 1993 | pmid = 8432910 | doi = 10.1002/cne.903270108 }}</ref>\n\n=== Localized cerebral cortex changes ===\nMRI detects localized [[cerebral cortex]] expansion after people learn complex tasks such as mirror reading (in this case in the right [[occipital cortex]]),<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ilg R, Wohlschl\u00e4ger AM, Gaser C | title = Gray matter increase induced by practice correlates with task-specific activation: a combined functional and morphometric magnetic resonance imaging study | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 28 | issue = 16 | pages = 4210\u20135 |date=April 2008 | pmid = 18417700 | pmc = 6670304 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.5722-07.2008 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> three-ball juggling (bilateral mid-[[Temporal lobe|temporal]] area and left posterior [[intraparietal sulcus]]),<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Draganski B, Gaser C, Busch V, Schuierer G, Bogdahn U, May A | title = Neuroplasticity: changes in grey matter induced by training | journal = Nature | volume = 427 | issue = 6972 | pages = 311\u20132 |date=January 2004 | pmid = 14737157 | doi = 10.1038/427311a }}</ref> and when medical students intensively revise for exams (bilaterally in the posterior and lateral [[parietal cortex]]).<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Draganski B, Gaser C, Kempermann G | title = Temporal and spatial dynamics of brain structure changes during extensive learning | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 26 | issue = 23 | pages = 6314\u20137 |date=June 2006 | pmid = 16763039 | pmc = 6675198 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4628-05.2006 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> Such changes in gray matter volume can be expected to link to changes in synapse numbers due to the increased numbers of glial cells and the expanded capillary vascularization needed to support their increased energy consumption.\n\n=== Institutional deprivation ===\nChildren that receive impoverished stimulation due to being confined to cots without social interaction or reliable caretakers in low quality [[orphanages]] show severe delays in cognitive and social development.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7610.1994.tb01220.x |vauthors=Kaler SR, Freeman BJ | title = Analysis of environmental deprivation: cognitive and social development in Romanian orphans | journal = J Child Psychol Psychiatry | volume = 35 | issue = 4 | pages = 769\u201381 |date=May 1994 | pmid = 7518826 }}</ref> 12% of them if adopted after 6 months of age show autistic or mildly autistic traits later at four years of age.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Rutter M, Andersen-Wood L, Beckett C | title = Quasi-autistic patterns following severe early global privation. English and Romanian Adoptees (ERA) Study Team | journal = J Child Psychol Psychiatry | volume = 40 | issue = 4 | pages = 537\u201349 |date=May 1999 | pmid = 10357161 | doi = 10.1017/S0021963099003935 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> Some children in such impoverished orphanages at two and half years of age still fail to produce intelligible words, though a year of foster care enabled such children to catch up in their language in most respects.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Windsor J, Glaze LE, Koga SF | title = Language acquisition with limited input: Romanian institution and foster care | journal = J. Speech Lang. Hear. Res. | volume = 50 | issue = 5 | pages = 1365\u201381 |date=October 2007 | pmid = 17905917 | doi = 10.1044/1092-4388(2007/095) }}</ref> Catch-up in other cognitive functioning also occurs after adoption, though problems continue in many children if this happens after the age of 6 months<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Beckett C, Maughan B, Rutter M | title = Do the effects of early severe deprivation on cognition persist into early adolescence? Findings from the English and Romanian adoptees study | journal = Child Dev | volume = 77 | issue = 3 | pages = 696\u2013711 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16686796 | doi = 10.1111/j.1467-8624.2006.00898.x |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\nSuch children show marked differences in their brains, consistent with research upon experiment animals, compared to children from normally stimulating environments. They have reduced brain activity in the [[Orbitofrontal cortex|orbital prefrontal cortex]], [[amygdala]], [[hippocampus]], [[temporal cortex]], and [[brain stem]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Chugani HT, Behen ME, Muzik O, Juh\u00e1sz C, Nagy F, Chugani DC | title = Local brain functional activity following early deprivation: a study of postinstitutionalized Romanian orphans | journal = NeuroImage | volume = 14 | issue = 6 | pages = 1290\u2013301 |date=December 2001 | pmid = 11707085 | doi = 10.1006/nimg.2001.0917 }}</ref> They also showed less developed [[white matter]] connections between different areas in their cerebral cortices, particularly the [[uncinate fasciculus]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Eluvathingal TJ, Chugani HT, Behen ME | title = Abnormal brain connectivity in children after early severe socioemotional deprivation: a diffusion tensor imaging study | journal = Pediatrics | volume = 117 | issue = 6 | pages = 2093\u2013100 |date=June 2006 | pmid = 16740852 | doi = 10.1542/peds.2005-1727 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\nConversely, enriching the experience of [[Premature birth|preterm infants]] with [[massage]] quickens the maturating of their [[EEG|electroencephalographic]] activity and their [[visual acuity]]. Moreover, as with enrichment in experimental animals, this associates with an increase in [[IGF-1]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Guzzetta A, Baldini S, Bancale A | title = Massage accelerates brain development and the maturation of visual function | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 29 | issue = 18 | pages = 6042\u201351 |date=May 2009 | pmid = 19420271 | pmc = 6665233 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.5548-08.2009 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n=== Cognitive reserve and resilience ===\nAnother source of evidence for the effect of environment stimulation upon the human brain is [[cognitive reserve]] (a measure of the brain's resilience to cognitive impairment) and the level of a person's education. Not only is higher education linked to a more cognitively demanding educational experience, but it also correlates with a person's general engagement in cognitively demanding activities.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1076/jcen.25.5.634.14572 |vauthors=Wilson R, Barnes L, Bennett D | title = Assessment of lifetime participation in cognitively stimulating activities | journal = J Clin Exp Neuropsychol | volume = 25 | issue = 5 | pages = 634\u201342 |date=August 2003 | pmid = 12815501 }}</ref> The more education a person has received, the less the effects of aging,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Corral M, Rodr\u00edguez M, Amenedo E, S\u00e1nchez JL, D\u00edaz F | title = Cognitive reserve, age, and neuropsychological performance in healthy participants | journal = Dev Neuropsychol | volume = 29 | issue = 3 | pages = 479\u201391 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16671863 | doi = 10.1207/s15326942dn2903_6 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Fritsch T, McClendon MJ, Smyth KA, Lerner AJ, Friedland RP, Larsen JD | title = Cognitive functioning in healthy aging: the role of reserve and lifestyle factors early in life | journal = Gerontologist | volume = 47 | issue = 3 | pages = 307\u201322 |date=June 2007 | pmid = 17565095 | doi = 10.1093/geront/47.3.307 }}</ref> dementia,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Hall CB, Derby C, LeValley A, Katz MJ, Verghese J, Lipton RB | title = Education delays accelerated decline on a memory test in persons who develop dementia | journal = Neurology | volume = 69 | issue = 17 | pages = 1657\u201364 |date=October 2007 | pmid = 17954781 | doi = 10.1212/01.wnl.0000278163.82636.30 }}</ref> white matter hyperintensities,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Nebes RD, Meltzer CC, Whyte EM | title = The relation of white matter hyperintensities to cognitive performance in the normal old: education matters | journal = Neuropsychol Dev Cogn B Aging Neuropsychol Cogn | volume = 13 | issue = 3\u20134 | pages = 326\u201340 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16887777 | doi = 10.1080/138255890969294 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> MRI-defined brain infarcts,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Elkins JS, Longstreth WT, Manolio TA, Newman AB, Bhadelia RA, Johnston SC | title = Education and the cognitive decline associated with MRI-defined brain infarct | journal = Neurology | volume = 67 | issue = 3 | pages = 435\u201340 |date=August 2006 | pmid = 16894104 | doi = 10.1212/01.wnl.0000228246.89109.98 }}</ref> Alzheimer's disease,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Koepsell TD, Kurland BF, Harel O, Johnson EA, Zhou XH, Kukull WA | title = Education, cognitive function, and severity of neuropathology in Alzheimer disease | journal = Neurology | volume = 70 | issue = 19 Pt 2 | pages = 1732\u20139 |date=May 2008 | pmid = 18160675 | doi = 10.1212/01.wnl.0000284603.85621.aa }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Roe CM, Mintun MA, D'Angelo G, Xiong C, Grant EA, Morris JC | title = Alzheimer's and Cognitive Reserve: Education Effect Varies with 11CPIB Uptake | journal = Arch. Neurol. | volume = 65 | issue = 11 | pages = 1467\u201371 |date=November 2008 | pmid = 19001165 | pmc = 2752218 | doi = 10.1001/archneur.65.11.1467  }}</ref> and traumatic brain injury.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1207/S15324826AN1003_04 |vauthors=Kesler SR, Adams HF, Blasey CM, Bigler ED | title = Premorbid intellectual functioning, education, and brain size in traumatic brain injury: an investigation of the cognitive reserve hypothesis | journal = Appl Neuropsychol | volume = 10 | issue = 3 | pages = 153\u201362 | year = 2003 | pmid = 12890641 }}</ref> Also, aging and dementia are less in those that engage in complex cognitive tasks.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Fratiglioni L, Paillard-Borg S, Winblad B | title = An active and socially integrated lifestyle in late life might protect against dementia | journal = Lancet Neurol | volume = 3 | issue = 6 | pages = 343\u201353 |date=June 2004 | pmid = 15157849 | doi = 10.1016/S1474-4422(04)00767-7 }}</ref> The cognitive decline of those with epilepsy could also be affected by the level of a person's education.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Pai MC, Tsai JJ | title = Is cognitive reserve applicable to epilepsy? The effect of educational level on the cognitive decline after onset of epilepsy | journal = Epilepsia | volume = 46 | issue = Suppl 1 | pages = 7\u201310 | year = 2005 | pmid = 15816971 | doi = 10.1111/j.0013-9580.2005.461003.x }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{col div|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Behavioral enrichment]]\n* [[Neural development]]\n* [[Neuroplasticity]]\n* [[Perceptual learning]]\n* [[Phenotypic plasticity]]\n* [[Rat Park]]\n* [[Stimulation]]\n* [[Synaptogenesis]]\n{{colend}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book | author = Diamond, Marian Cleeves | title = Enriching Heredity: The Impact of the Environment on the Anatomy of the Brain | publisher = Free Press | location = New York | year = 1988 | isbn = 978-0-02-907431-2 | author-link = Marian Diamond }}\n* {{cite book | author = Jensen, Eric | title = Enriching the Brain: How to maximize every learner's potential | publisher = Jossey-Bass, A John Wiley & Sons Imprint | location = San Francisco | year = 2006 | isbn = 978-0-7879-7547-0 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/enrichingbrainho00jens }}\n* {{cite book | vauthors = Renner MJ, Rosenzweig MR | title = Enriched and Impoverished Environments: Effects on Brain and Behavior | publisher = Springer-Verlag | location = New York | year = 1987 | isbn = 978-3-540-96523-7 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.newhorizons.org/neuro/diamond_enrich.htm The Significance of Enrichment]\n\n[[Category:Behavioral neuroscience]]\n[[Category:Cognitive neuroscience]]\n[[Category:Developmental biology]]\n[[Category:Developmental neuroscience]]\n[[Category:Developmental psychology]]\n[[Category:Educational psychology]]\n[[Category:Human development]]\n[[Category:Learning]]\n[[Category:Neurophysiology]]\n[[Category:Neuropsychology]]\n[[Category:Personal development]]\n[[Category:Rehabilitation medicine]]\n[[Category:Developmental psychiatry]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Behavioral enrichment}}\n[[File:Rat coming out cage.jpg|thumb|300px| A rodent is not stimulated by the environment in a wire cage, and this affects its brain negatively, particularly the complexity of its synaptic connections]]\n'''Environmental enrichment''' is the stimulation of the [[brain]] by its physical and social surroundings. Brains in richer, more stimulating environments have higher rates of [[synaptogenesis]] and more complex [[dendrites|dendrite arbors]], leading to increased brain activity. This effect takes place primarily during [[neurodevelopment]], but also during adulthood  to a lesser degree. With extra [[synapses]] there is also increased synapse activity, leading to an increased size and number of [[glia]]l energy-support cells. Environmental enrichment also enhances [[capillary]] vasculation, providing the neurons and glial cells with extra energy. The [[neuropil]] (neurons, glial cells, capillaries, combined together) expands, thickening the cortex. Research on rodent brains suggests that environmental enrichment may also lead to an increased rate of [[neurogenesis]].\n\nResearch on animals finds that environmental enrichment could aid the treatment and recovery of numerous brain-related dysfunctions, including [[Alzheimer's disease]] and those connected to [[aging]], whereas a lack of stimulation might impair cognitive development. Moreover, this research also suggests that environmental enrichment leads to a greater level of [[cognitive reserve]], the brain's resilience to the effects of conditions such as [[aging]] and [[dementia]].\n\nResearch on humans suggests that lack of stimulation delays and impairs cognitive development. Research also finds that attaining and engaging in higher levels of education, environments in which people participate in more challenging cognitively stimulating activities, results in greater cognitive reserve.\n\n== Early research ==\n[[Donald O. Hebb]] in 1947 found that rats raised as pets performed better on problem solving tests than rats raised in cages.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Hebb DO | title = The effects of early experience on problem solving at maturity | journal = American Psychologist | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = 306\u20137 | year = 1947 | doi = 10.1037/h0063667 }}</ref> His research, however, did not investigate the brain nor use standardized impoverished and enriched environments. Research doing this first was started in 1960 at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] by [[Mark Rosenzweig (psychologist)|Mark Rosenzweig]], who compared single rats in normal cages, and those placed in ones with toys, ladders, tunnels, running wheels in groups. This found that growing up in enriched environments affected enzyme [[cholinesterase]] activity.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1037/h0045402 |vauthors=Krech D, Rosenzweig MR, Bennett EL | title = Effects of environmental complexity and training on brain chemistry | journal = J Comp Physiol Psychol | volume = 53 | pages = 509\u201319 |date=December 1960 | pmid = 13754181 | issue = 6 }}</ref> This work led in 1962 to the discovery that environmental enrichment increased [[cerebral cortex]] volume.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1037/h0041137 |vauthors=Rosenzweig MR, Krech D, Bennett EL, Diamond MC | title = Effects of environmental complexity and training on brain chemistry and anatomy: a replication and extension | journal = J Comp Physiol Psychol | volume = 55 | pages = 429\u201337 |date=August 1962 | pmid = 14494091 | issue = 4 |url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/8h919150}}<!--http://www.escholarship.org/uc/item/8h919150 --></ref> In 1964, it was found that this was due to increased cerebral cortex thickness and greater [[synapse]] and [[glial]] numbers.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1038/2041161a0 |vauthors=Altman J, Das GD | title = Autoradiographic Examination of the Effects of Enriched Environment on the Rate of Glial Multiplication in the Adult Rat Brain | journal = Nature | volume = 204 | pages = 1161\u20133 |date=December 1964 | pmid = 14264369 | issue = 4964 }}</ref><ref name=\"DiamondKrech\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1002/cne.901230110 |vauthors=Diamond MC, Krech D, Rosenzweig MR | title = The Effects of an Enriched Environment on the Histology of the Rat Cerebral Cortex | journal = J. Comp. Neurol. | volume = 123 | pages = 111\u201320 |date=August 1964 | pmid = 14199261 }}</ref>\n\nAlso starting around 1960, [[Harry Harlow]] studied the effects of [[maternal deprivation|maternal and social deprivation]] on [[rhesus monkey]] infants (a form of environmental stimulus deprivation). This established the importance of social stimulation for normal [[cognitive development|cognitive]] and emotional development.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Harlow HF, Rowland GL, Griffin GA | title = The Effect of Total Social Deprivation on the Development of Monkey Behavior | journal = Psychiatr Res Rep Am Psychiatr Assoc | volume = 19 | pages = 116\u201335 |date=December 1964 | pmid = 14232649 }}</ref>\n\n== Synapses ==\n\n=== Synaptogenesis ===\n\nRats raised with environmental enrichment have thicker cerebral cortices (3.3\u20137%) that contain 25% more [[synapses]].<ref name=\"DiamondKrech\" /><ref name=\"DiamondLaw\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Diamond MC, Law F, Rhodes H | title = Increases in cortical depth and glia numbers in rats subjected to enriched environment | journal = J. Comp. Neurol. | volume = 128 | issue = 1 | pages = 117\u201326 |date=September 1966 | pmid = 4165855 | doi = 10.1002/cne.901280110 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> This effect of environmental richness upon the brain occurs whether it is experienced immediately following birth,<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.167.3916.292 |vauthors=Schapiro S, Vukovich KR | title = Early experience effects upon cortical dendrites: a proposed model for development | journal = Science | volume = 167 | issue = 3916 | pages = 292\u20134 |date=January 1970 | pmid = 4188192 }}</ref> after weaning,<ref name=\"DiamondKrech\" /><ref name=\"DiamondLaw\" /><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Bennett EL, Diamond MC, Krech D, Rosenzweig MR | title = Chemical and Anatomical Plasticity Brain | journal = Science | volume = 146 | pages = 610\u20139 |date=October 1964 | pmid = 14191699 | doi = 10.1126/science.146.3644.610 | issue = 3644 }}</ref> or during maturity.<ref name=\"Briones\" >{{cite journal |vauthors=Briones TL, Klintsova AY, Greenough WT | title = Stability of synaptic plasticity in the adult rat visual cortex induced by complex environment exposure | journal = Brain Res. | volume = 1018 | issue = 1 | pages = 130\u20135 |date=August 2004 | pmid = 15262214 | doi = 10.1016/j.brainres.2004.06.001 }}</ref> When synapse numbers increase in adults, they can remain high in number even when the adults are returned to impoverished environment for 30 days<ref name=\"Briones\" /> suggesting that such increases in synapse numbers are not necessarily temporary. However, the increase in synapse numbers has been observed generally to reduce with maturation.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Holtmaat AJ, Trachtenberg JT, Wilbrecht L | title = Transient and persistent dendritic spines in the neocortex in vivo | journal = Neuron | volume = 45 | issue = 2 | pages = 279\u201391 |date=January 2005 | pmid = 15664179 | doi = 10.1016/j.neuron.2005.01.003 |display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Zuo Y, Lin A, Chang P, Gan WB | title = Development of long-term dendritic brain stability in diverse regions of cerebral cortex | journal = Neuron | volume = 46 | issue = 2 | pages = 181\u20139 |date=April 2005 | pmid = 15848798 | doi = 10.1016/j.neuron.2005.04.001 }}</ref> Stimulation affects not only synapses upon [[pyramidal neuron]]s (the main projecting neurons in the cerebral cortex) but also [[stellate cell|stellate]] ones (that are usually [[interneurons]]).<ref name=\"Greenough\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0014-4886(73)90090-3 |vauthors=Greenough WT, Volkmar FR | title = Pattern of dendritic branching in occipital cortex of rats reared in complex environments | journal = Exp. Neurol. | volume = 40 | issue = 2 | pages = 491\u2013504 |date=August 1973 | pmid = 4730268 }}</ref> It can also affect neurons outside the brain, such as those in the [[retina]].<ref name=\"Landi, S. 2007\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Landi S, Sale A, Berardi N, Viegi A, Maffei L, Cenni MC | title = Retinal functional development is sensitive to environmental enrichment: a role for BDNF | journal = FASEB J. | volume = 21 | issue = 1 | pages = 130\u20139 |date=January 2007 | pmid = 17135370 | doi = 10.1096/fj.06-6083com | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c5897cdbaa09aec195892d6740faa002aea460f8 }}</ref>\n\n=== Dendrite complexity ===\nEnvironmental enrichment affects the complexity and length of the [[dendrite]] arbors (upon which synapses form). Higher-order dendrite branch complexity is increased in enriched environments,<ref name=\"Greenough\" /><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.176.4042.1445 |vauthors=Volkmar FR, Greenough WT | title = Rearing complexity affects branching of dendrites in the visual cortex of the rat | journal = Science | volume = 176 | issue = 4042 | pages = 1445\u20137 |date=June 1972 | pmid = 5033647 }}</ref> as can the length, in young animals, of distal branches.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0163-1047(92)90937-Y |vauthors=Wallace CS, Kilman VL, Withers GS, Greenough WT | title = Increases in dendritic length in occipital cortex after 4 days of differential housing in weanling rats | journal = Behav. Neural Biol. | volume = 58 | issue = 1 | pages = 64\u20138 |date=July 1992 | pmid = 1417672 }}</ref>\n\n=== Activity and energy consumption ===\nAnimals in enriched environments show evidence of increased synapse activation.<ref name=\"Sirevaag\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Sirevaag AM, Greenough WT | title = Differential rearing effects on rat visual cortex synapses. III. Neuronal and glial nuclei, boutons, dendrites, and capillaries | journal = Brain Res. | volume = 424 | issue = 2 | pages = 320\u201332 |date=October 1987 | pmid = 3676831 | doi = 10.1016/0006-8993(87)91477-6}}</ref> Synapses tend to also be much larger.<ref name=\"sievaag85\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Sirevaag AM, Greenough WT | title = Differential rearing effects on rat visual cortex synapses. II. Synaptic morphometry | journal = Brain Res. | volume = 351 | issue = 2 | pages = 215\u201326 |date=April 1985 | pmid = 3995348 | doi = 10.1016/0165-3806(85)90193-2}}</ref> [[Gamma wave|Gamma oscillations]] become larger in amplitude in the hippocampus.<ref name=\"Shinohara\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1038/ncomms2658 |vauthors=Shinohara Y, Hosoya A, Hirase H | title = Experience enhances gamma oscillations and interhemispheric asymmetry in the hippocampus | journal = Nat Commun | volume = 4 | pages = 1652 |date=April 2013 | pmid = 23552067 | issue=4 | pmc=3644069}}</ref> This increased energy consumption is reflected in glial and local capillary vasculation that provides synapses with extra energy.\n* Glial cell numbers per neuron increase 12\u201314%<ref name=\"DiamondKrech\" /><ref name=\"DiamondLaw\" />\n* The direct apposition area of glial cells with synapses expands by 19%<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Jones TA, Greenough WT | title = Ultrastructural evidence for increased contact between astrocytes and synapses in rats reared in a complex environment | journal = Neurobiol Learn Mem | volume = 65 | issue = 1 | pages = 48\u201356 |date=January 1996 | pmid = 8673406 | doi = 10.1006/nlme.1996.0005 }}</ref>\n* The volume of glial cell nuclei for each synapse is higher by 37.5%<ref name=\"Sirevaag\" />\n* The mean volume of mitochondria per neuron is 20% greater<ref name=\"Sirevaag\" />\n* The volume of glial cell nuclei for each neuron is 63% higher<ref name=\"Sirevaag\" />\n* Capillary density is increased.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Borowsky IW, Collins RC | title = Metabolic anatomy of brain: a comparison of regional capillary density, glucose metabolism, and enzyme activities | journal = J. Comp. Neurol. | volume = 288 | issue = 3 | pages = 401\u201313 |date=October 1989 | pmid = 2551935 | doi = 10.1002/cne.902880304 }}</ref>\n* Capillaries are wider (4.35 \u03bcm compared to 4.15 \u03bcm in controls)<ref name=\"Sirevaag\" />\n* Shorter distance exist between any part of the [[neuropil]] and a capillary (27.6 \u03bcm compared to 34.6 \u03bcm)<ref name=\"Sirevaag\" />\nThese energy related changes to the [[neuropil]] are responsible for increasing the volume of the cerebral cortex (the increase in synapse numbers contributes in itself hardly any extra volume).\n\n=== Motor learning stimulation ===\nPart of the effect of environmental enrichment is providing opportunities to acquire [[motor skills]]. Research on rats learning an \u201cacrobatic\u201d skill shows that such learning activity leads to increased synapse count.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1073/pnas.87.14.5568 |vauthors=Black JE, Isaacs KR, Anderson BJ, Alcantara AA, Greenough WT | title = Learning causes synaptogenesis, whereas motor activity causes angiogenesis, in cerebellar cortex of adult rats | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 87 | issue = 14 | pages = 5568\u201372 |date=July 1990 | pmid = 1695380 | pmc = 54366 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kleim JA, Hogg TM, VandenBerg PM, Cooper NR, Bruneau R, Remple M | title = Cortical synaptogenesis and motor map reorganization occur during late, but not early, phase of motor skill learning | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 24 | issue = 3 | pages = 628\u201333 |date=January 2004 | pmid = 14736848 | pmc = 6729261 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.3440-03.2004 }}</ref>\n\n=== Maternal transmission ===\nEnvironmental enrichment during [[pregnancy]] has effects upon the [[fetus]], such as accelerating his or her retinal development.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Sale A, Cenni MC, Ciucci F, Putignano E, Chierzi S, Maffei L| title = Maternal Enrichment during Pregnancy Accelerates Retinal Development of the Fetus | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 2 | issue = 11 | pages = e1160 | year = 2007 | pmid = 18000533 | pmc = 2063464 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0001160 | editor1-last = Reh | editor1-first = Thomas }} {{open access}}</ref>\n\n== Neurogenesis ==\nEnvironmental enrichment can also lead to the [[neurogenesis|formation of neurons]] (at least in rats)<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Fan Y, Liu Z, Weinstein PR, Fike JR, Liu J | title = Environmental enrichment enhances neurogenesis and improves functional outcome after cranial irradiation | journal = Eur. J. Neurosci. | volume = 25 | issue = 1 | pages = 38\u201346 |date=January 2007 | pmid = 17241265 | doi = 10.1111/j.1460-9568.2006.05269.x }}</ref> and reverse both the loss of neurons in the [[hippocampus]] and memory impairment from chronic stress.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Veena J, Srikumar BN, Mahati K, Bhagya V, Raju TR, Shankaranarayana Rao BS | title = Enriched environment restores hippocampal cell proliferation and ameliorates cognitive deficits in chronically stressed rats | journal = J. Neurosci. Res. | volume = 87 | issue = 4 | pages = 831\u201343 |date=March 2009 | pmid = 19006089 | doi = 10.1002/jnr.21907 }}</ref> However, its relevance has been questioned for the behavioral effects of enriched environments.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Meshi D, Drew MR, Saxe M | title = Hippocampal neurogenesis is not required for behavioral effects of environmental enrichment | journal = Nat. Neurosci. | volume = 9 | issue = 6 | pages = 729\u201331 |date=June 2006 | pmid = 16648847 | doi = 10.1038/nn1696 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n== Mechanisms ==\n\nEnriched environments affect the expression of [[genes]] that determine neuronal structure in the cerebral cortex and hippocampus.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Rampon C, Jiang CH, Dong H | title = Effects of environmental enrichment on gene expression in the brain | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 97 | issue = 23 | pages = 12880\u20134 |date=November 2000 | pmid = 11070096 | pmc = 18858 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.97.23.12880 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> At the molecular level, this occurs through increased concentrations of the [[neurotrophins]] [[Nerve growth factor|NGF]], [[NT-3]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ickes BR, Pham TM, Sanders LA, Albeck DS, Mohammed AH, Granholm AC | title = Long-term environmental enrichment leads to regional increases in neurotrophin levels in rat brain | journal = Exp. Neurol. | volume = 164 | issue = 1 | pages = 45\u201352 |date=July 2000 | pmid = 10877914 | doi = 10.1006/exnr.2000.7415 }}</ref><ref name=\"Torasdotter, M. 1998\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0166-4328(97)00142-3 |vauthors=Torasdotter M, Metsis M, Henriksson BG, Winblad B, Mohammed AH | title = Environmental enrichment results in higher levels of nerve growth factor mRNA in the rat visual cortex and hippocampus | journal = Behav. Brain Res. | volume = 93 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 83\u201390 |date=June 1998 | pmid = 9659990 }}</ref> and changes in [[BDNF]].<ref name=\"Landi, S. 2007\" /><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Zhu SW, Codita A, Bogdanovic N | title = Influence of environmental manipulation on exploratory behaviour in male BDNF knockout mice | journal = Behav. Brain Res. | volume = 197 | issue = 2 | pages = 339\u201346 |date=February 2009 | pmid = 18951926 | doi = 10.1016/j.bbr.2008.09.032 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> This alters the activation of [[cholinergic]] neurons,<ref name=\"Torasdotter, M. 1998\" /> [[5-HT]],<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0169-328X(97)00317-3 |vauthors=Rasmuson S, Olsson T, Henriksson BG | title = Environmental enrichment selectively increases 5-HT1A receptor mRNA expression and binding in the rat hippocampus | journal = Brain Res. Mol. Brain Res. | volume = 53 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 285\u201390 |date=January 1998 | pmid = 9473697 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> and [[Adrenergic receptor|beta-adrenolin]].<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1006/nlme.1995.1043 |vauthors=Escorihuela RM, Fern\u00e1ndez-Teruel A, Tobe\u00f1a A | title = Early environmental stimulation produces long-lasting changes on beta-adrenoceptor transduction system | journal = Neurobiol Learn Mem | volume = 64 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201357 |date=July 1995 | pmid = 7582812 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> Another effect is to increase proteins such as [[synaptophysin]] and [[DLG4|PSD-95]] in synapses.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Nithianantharajah J, Levis H, Murphy M | title = Environmental enrichment results in cortical and subcortical changes in levels of synaptophysin and PSD-95 proteins | journal = Neurobiol Learn Mem | volume = 81 | issue = 3 | pages = 200\u201310 |date=May 2004 | pmid = 15082021 | doi = 10.1016/j.nlm.2004.02.002 }}</ref> Changes in [[Wnt signaling pathway|Wnt signaling]] have also been found to mimic in adult mice the effects of environmental enrichment upon synapses in the hippocampus.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Gogolla N, Galimberti I, Deguchi Y, Caroni P | title = Wnt signaling mediates experience-related regulation of synapse numbers and mossy fiber connectivities in the adult hippocampus | journal = Neuron | volume = 62 | issue = 4 | pages = 510\u201325 |date=May 2009 | pmid = 19477153 | doi = 10.1016/j.neuron.2009.04.022 }}</ref> Increase in neurons numbers could be linked to changes in [[Vascular endothelial growth factor|VEGF]].<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.2174/156720506775697133 | vauthors = During MJ, Cao L | title = VEGF, a mediator of the effect of experience on hippocampal neurogenesis | journal = Curr Alzheimer Res | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | pages = 29\u201333 | date = February 2006 | pmid = 16472200 | url = http://www.bentham-direct.org/pages/content.php?CAR/2006/00000003/00000001/007AT.SGM | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120722155514/http://www.bentham-direct.org/pages/content.php?CAR/2006/00000003/00000001/007AT.SGM | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2012-07-22 }}</ref>\n\n== Rehabilitation and resilience ==\n\nResearch in animals suggests that environmental enrichment aids  recovery from certain neurological disorders and cognitive impairments. There are two mains areas of focus: neurological rehabilitation and [[cognitive reserve]], the brain's resistance to the effects of exposure to physical, natural, and social threats. Although most of these experiments used animal subjects, mainly rodents, researchers have pointed to the affected areas of animal brains to which human brains are most similar and used their findings as evidence to show that humans would have comparable reactions to enriched environments. The tests done on animals are thus meant to represent human simulations for the following list of conditions.\n\n===Neurological rehabilitation===\n\n====Autism====\n\nA study conducted in 2011 led to the conclusion that environmental enrichment vastly improves the cognitive ability of children with [[autism]]. The study found that autistic children who receive [[olfactory stimulation|olfactory]] and [[tactile stimulation]] along with [[exercises]] that stimulated other paired sensory modalities clinically improved by 42 percent while autistic children not receiving this treatment clinically improved by just 7 percent.<ref name = Woo>{{cite journal |vauthors=Woo CC, Leon M |title=Environmental Enrichment as an Effective Treatment for Autism: A Randomized Controlled Trial |journal=Behav Neurosci |volume=127 |issue=4 |pages=487\u201397 |date=March 2011 |pmid=23688137 |doi=10.1037/a0033010 |url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/5zf6s24x }}</ref> The same study also showed that there was significant clinical improvement in autistic children exposed to enriched sensorimotor environments, and a vast majority of parents reported that their child's quality of life was much better with the treatment.<ref name = Woo/>  A second study confirmed its effectiveness.  The second study also found after 6 months of sensory enrichment therapy, 21% of the children who initially had been given an autism classification, using the Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule, improved to the point that, although they remained on the autism spectrum, they no longer met the criteria for classic autism. None of the standard care controls reached an equivalent level of improvement.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Woo, Cynthia C. |author2=Donnelly, Joseph H. |author3=Steinberg-Epstein, Robin |author4=Leon, Michael | title=Environmental enrichment as a therapy for autism: A clinical trial replication and extension |journal=Behavioral Neuroscience |pages= 412\u2013422|date=Aug 2015 |pmid= 26052790|doi=10.1037/bne0000068 |volume=129 |issue=4 |pmc=4682896}}</ref> The therapy using the methodologies is titled [[Sensory Enrichment Therapy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.webmd.com/brain/autism/news/20130605/sensory-focused-autism-therapy-shows-early-promise |title='Sensory-Focused' Autism Therapy Shows Early Promise |author=Mary Brophy Marcus |date=June 5, 2013 |website=webmd.com |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ksl.com/?sid=31896222&nid=148&title=autism-treatment-gives-utah-family-hope |title=Autism treatment gives Utah family hope |author=Nkoyo Iyamba |date=October 9, 2014 |website=ksl.com |publisher= |access-date= |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925105355/https://www.ksl.com/?sid=31896222&nid=148&title=autism-treatment-gives-utah-family-hope |archive-date=September 25, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Alzheimer's disease====\n\nThrough environmental enrichment, researchers were able to enhance and partially repair memory deficits in mice between ages of 2 to 7 months with characteristics of [[Alzheimer's disease]]. Mice in enriched environments performed significantly better on object recognition tests and the [[Morris water navigation task|Morris Water Maze]] than they had when they were in standard environments. It was thus concluded that environmental enrichment enhances visual and learning memory for those with Alzheimer's.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Berardi N, Braschi C, Capsoni S, Cattaneo A, Maffei L |title=Environmental enrichment delays the onset of memory deficits and reduces neuropathological hallmarks in a mouse model of Alzheimer-like neurodegeneration |journal=J. Alzheimers Dis. |volume=11 |issue=3 |pages=359\u201370 |date=June 2007 |pmid=17851186 |url=http://iospress.metapress.com/openurl.asp?genre=article&issn=1387-2877&volume=11&issue=3&spage=359 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120720095948/http://iospress.metapress.com/openurl.asp?genre=article&issn=1387-2877&volume=11&issue=3&spage=359 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-20 |doi=10.3233/JAD-2007-11312 }}</ref> Furthermore, it has been found that mouse models of Alzheimer's disease that were exposed to enriched environment before amyloid onset (at 3 months of age) and then returned to their home cage for over 7 months, showed preserved spatial memory and reduced amyloid deposition at 13 months old, when they are supposed to show dramatic memory deficits and amyloid plaque load. These findings reveal the preventive, and long-lasting effects of early life stimulating experience on Alzheimer-like pathology in mice and likely reflect the capacity of enriched environment to efficiently stimulate the [[cognitive reserve]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Verret L, Krezymon A, Halley H, Trouche S, Zerwas M, Lazouret M, Lassalle JM, Rampon C | title = Transient enriched housing before amyloidosis onset sustains cognitive improvement in Tg2576 mice | journal = Neurobiology of Aging | volume = 34 | issue = 1 | pages = 211\u201325 |date=Jan 2013 | pmid = 22727275 | doi=10.1016/j.neurobiolaging.2012.05.013}}</ref>\n\n====Huntington's disease====\n\nResearch has indicated that environmental enrichment can help relieve motor and psychiatric deficits caused by [[Huntington's disease]]. It also improves lost protein levels for those with the disease, and prevents striatal and hippocampal deficits in the [[BDNF]], located in the hippocampus.<ref name = Spires>{{cite journal |vauthors=Spires TL, Grote HE, Varshney NK | title = Environmental enrichment rescues protein deficits in a mouse model of Huntington's disease, indicating a possible disease mechanism | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 24 | issue = 9 | pages = 2270\u20136 |date=March 2004 | pmid = 14999077 | pmc = 6730435 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.1658-03.2004 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> These findings have led researchers to suggest that environmental enrichment has a potential to be a possible form of therapy for those with Huntington's.<ref name = Spires/>\n\n====Parkinson's disease====\n\nMultiple studies have reported that environmental enrichment for adult mice helps relieve neuronal death, which is particularly beneficial to those with [[Parkinson's disease]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Faherty CJ, Raviie Shepherd K, Herasimtschuk A, Smeyne RJ | title = Environmental enrichment in adulthood eliminates neuronal death in experimental Parkinsonism | journal = Brain Res. Mol. Brain Res. | volume = 134 | issue = 1 | pages = 170\u20139 |date=March 2005 | pmid = 15790541 | doi = 10.1016/j.molbrainres.2004.08.008 }}</ref> A more recent study shows that environmental enrichment particularly affects the [[nigrostriatal pathway]], which is important for managing [[dopamine]] and acetylcholine levels, critical for motor deficits.<ref name = Goldberg>{{cite journal|last=Goldberg|first=NR|author2=Fields, V |author3=Pflibsen, L |author4=Salvatore, MF |author5= Meshul, CK |title=Social enrichment attenuates nigrostriatal lesioning and reverses motor impairment in a progressive 1-methyl-2-phenyl-1,2,3,6-tetrahydropyridine (MPTP) mouse model of Parkinson's disease.|journal=Neurobiology of Disease|date=March 2012|volume=45|issue=3|pages=1051\u201367|pmid=22198503|doi=10.1016/j.nbd.2011.12.024}}</ref>  Moreover, it was found that environmental enrichment has beneficial effects for the social implications of Parkinson's disease.<ref name = Goldberg/>\n\n====Stroke====\n\nResearch done in animals has shown that subjects recovering in an enriched environment 15 days after having a [[stroke]] had significantly improved neurobehavioral function. In addition these same subjects showed greater capability of learning and larger infarct post-intervention than those who were not in an enriched environment. It was thus concluded that environmental enrichment had a considerable beneficial effect on the learning and sensorimotor functions on animals post-stroke.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Janssen H, Bernhardt J, Collier JM, Sena ES, McElduff P, Attia J, Pollack M, Howells DW, Nilsson M, Calford MB, Spratt NJ |title=An Enriched Environment Improves Sensorimotor Function Post-Ischemic Stroke|journal=Neurorehabilitation and Neural Repair|date=12 September 2010|volume=24|issue=9|pages=802\u2013813|doi=10.1177/1545968310372092|pmid=20834046|url=https://www.pure.ed.ac.uk/ws/files/8123036/Janssen_et_al_2010.pdf}}<!--https://www.pure.ed.ac.uk/ws/files/8123036/Janssen_et_al_2010.pdf--></ref> A 2013 study also found that environmental enrichment socially benefits patients recovering from stroke. Researchers in that study concluded that stroke patients in enriched environments in assisted-care facilities are much more likely to be engaging with other patients during normal social hours instead of being alone or sleeping.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Janssen|first=Heidi|author2=Ada, Louise |author3=Bernhardt, Julie |author4=McElduff, Patrick |author5=Pollack, Michael |author6=Nilsson, Michael |author7= Spratt, Neil J. |title=An enriched environment increases activity in stroke patients undergoing rehabilitation in a mixed rehabilitation unit: a pilot non-randomized controlled trial|journal=Disability and Rehabilitation|date=29 April 2013|pages=255\u2013262|doi=10.3109/09638288.2013.788218|pmid=23627534 |volume=36 |issue=3}}</ref>\n\n====Rett syndrome====\n\nA 2008 study found that environmental enrichment was significant in aiding recovery of motor coordination and some recovery of BDNF levels in female mice with conditions similar to those of [[Rett syndrome]]. Over the course of 30 weeks female mice in enriched environments showed superior ability in motor coordination to those in standard conditions.<ref name = Kondo>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kondo M, Gray LJ, Pelka GJ, Christodoulou J, Tam PP, Hannan AJ | title = Environmental enrichment ameliorates a motor coordination deficit in a mouse model of Rett syndrome--Mecp2 gene dosage effects and BDNF expression | journal = Eur. J. Neurosci. | volume = 27 | issue = 12 | pages = 3342\u201350 |date=June 2008 | pmid = 18557922 | doi = 10.1111/j.1460-9568.2008.06305.x }}</ref> Although they were unable to have full motor capability, they were able to prevent a more severe motor deficit by living in an enriched environment. These results combined with increased levels of BDNF in the cerebellum led researchers to conclude that an enriched environment that stimulates areas of the motor cortex and areas of the cerebellum having to do with motor learning is beneficial in aiding mice with Rett syndrome.<ref name = Kondo/>\n\n====Amblyopia====\n\nA recent study found that adult rats with [[amblyopia]] improved visual acuity two weeks after being placed into an enriched environment.<ref name = Sale>{{cite journal |vauthors=Sale A, Maya Vetencourt JF, Medini P | title = Environmental enrichment in adulthood promotes amblyopia recovery through a reduction of intracortical inhibition | journal = Nat. Neurosci. | volume = 10 | issue = 6 | pages = 679\u201381 |date=June 2007 | pmid = 17468749 | doi = 10.1038/nn1899 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> The same study showed that another two weeks after ending environmental enrichment, the rats retained their visual acuity improvement. Conversely, rats in a standard environment showed no improvement in visual acuity. It was thus concluded that environmental enrichment reduces GABA inhibition and increases BDNF expression in the visual cortex. As a result, the growth and development of neurons and synapses in the visual cortex were much improved due to the enriched environment.<ref name = Sale/>\n\n====Sensory deprivation====\n\nStudies have shown that with the help of environmental enrichment the effects of [[sensory deprivation]] can be corrected. For example, a visual impairment known as \"dark-rearing\" in the visual cortex can be prevented and rehabilitated. In general, an enriched environment will  improve, if not repair, the sensory systems animals possess.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7580.2009.01103.x |vauthors=Argando\u00f1a EG, Bengoetxea H, Lafuente JV | title = Physical exercise is required for environmental enrichment to offset the quantitative effects of dark-rearing on the S-100\u03b2 astrocytic density in the rat visual cortex | journal = Journal of Anatomy | volume = 215 | issue = 2 | pages = 132\u2013140 | year = 2009 | pmid = 19500177 | pmc = 2740960 }}</ref>\n\n====Lead poisoning====\n\nDuring development, [[gestation]] is one of the most critical periods for exposure to any lead. Exposure to high levels of lead at this time can lead to inferior spatial learning performance. Studies have shown that environmental enrichment can overturn damage to the hippocampus induced by [[lead poisoning|lead exposure]].<ref name = Cao>{{cite journal|last=Cao|first=Xiujing|author2=Huang, Shenghai |author3=Ruan, Diyun |title=Enriched environment restores impaired hippocampal long-term potentiation and water maze performance induced by developmental lead exposure in rats|journal=Developmental Psychobiology|date=April 2008|volume=50|issue=3|pages=307\u2013313|doi=10.1002/dev.20287|pmid=18335502}}</ref>  Learning and spatial memory that are dependent on the long-term potentiation of the hippocampus are vastly improve as subjects in an enriched environments had lower levels of lead concentration in their hippocampi. The findings also showed that enriched environments result in some natural protection of lead-induced brain deficits.<ref name = Cao/>\n\n====Chronic spinal cord injuries====\n\nResearch has indicated that animals suffering from [[spinal cord injuries]] showed significant improvement in motor capabilities even with a long delay in treatment after the injury when exposed to environmental enrichment.<ref name = Fischer>{{cite journal |vauthors=Fischer FR, Peduzzi JD | title = Functional Recovery in Rats With Chronic Spinal Cord Injuries After Exposure to an Enriched Environment | journal = J Spinal Cord Med | volume = 30 | issue = 2 | pages = 147\u201355 | year = 2007 | pmid = 17591227 | pmc = 2031947 | doi = 10.1080/10790268.2007.11753926 }}</ref> Social interactions, exercise, and novelty all play major roles in aiding the recovery of an injured subject. This has led to some suggestions that the spinal cord has a continued plasticity and all efforts must be made for enriched environments to stimulate this plasticity in order to aid recovery.<ref name = Fischer/>\n\n====Maternal deprivation stress====\n\n[[Maternal deprivation]] can be caused by the abandonment by a nurturing parent at a young age. In rodents or nonhuman primates, this leads to a higher vulnerability for\nstress-related illness.<ref name = Francis>{{cite journal |vauthors=Francis DD, Diorio J, Plotsky PM, Meaney MJ | title = Environmental enrichment reverses the effects of maternal separation on stress reactivity | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 22 | issue = 18 | pages = 7840\u20133 |date=September 2002 | pmid = 12223535 | pmc = 6758090 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.22-18-07840.2002 }}</ref> Research suggests that environmental enrichment can reverse the effects of maternal separation on stress reactivity, possibly by affecting the hippocampus and the prefrontal cortex.<ref name = Francis/>\n\n====Child neglect====\n\nIn all children, maternal care is one of the significant influences for hippocampal development, providing the foundation for stable and individualized learning and memory. However, this is not the case for those who have experienced [[child neglect]]. Researchers determined that through environmental enrichment, a neglected child can partially receive the same hippocampal development and stability, albeit not at the same level as that of the presence of a parent or guardian.<ref name = Bredy>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0306-4522(02)00918-1 |vauthors=Bredy TW, Humpartzoomian RA, Cain DP, Meaney MJ | title = Partial reversal of the effect of maternal care on cognitive function through environmental enrichment | journal = Neuroscience | volume = 118 | issue = 2 | pages = 571\u20136 | year = 2003 | pmid = 12699791 }}</ref> The results were comparable to those of child intervention programs, rendering environmental enrichment a useful method for dealing with child neglect.<ref name = Bredy/>{{failed verification|I do not have access to full article, but it describes a study with rats, in which the effects of being raised by mothers with low licking/grooming behavior were reversed through environmental enrichment at the behavioral level but not at the physiological level.|date=January 2014}}\n\n=== Cognitive reserve ===\n\n====Aging====\n\nDecreased hippocampal neurogenesis is a characteristic of [[aging]]. Environmental enrichment increases neurogenesis in aged rodents by potentiating neuronal differentiation and new cell survival.<ref name = Kumar>{{cite journal|last=Speisman|first=RB|author2=Kumar, A |author3=Rani, A |author4=Pastoriza, JM |author5=Severance, JE |author6=Foster, TC |author7= Ormerod, BK |title=Environmental enrichment restores neurogenesis and rapid acquisition in aged rats.|journal=Neurobiology of Aging|date=January 2013|volume=34|issue=1|pages=263\u201374|pmid=22795793|doi=10.1016/j.neurobiolaging.2012.05.023 |pmc=3480541}}</ref> As a result, subjects exposed to environmental enrichment aged better due to superior ability in retaining their levels of spatial and learning memory.<ref name = Kumar/>\n\n====Prenatal and perinatal cocaine exposure====\n\nResearch has shown that mice exposed to environmental enrichment are less affected by the consequences of [[Cocaine#Effects in pregnancy and nursing|cocaine exposure]] in comparison with those in standard environments. Although the levels of dopamine in the brains of both sets of mice were relatively similar, when both subjects were exposed to the cocaine injection, mice in enriched environment were significantly less responsive than those in standard environments.<ref name = Solinas>{{cite journal |vauthors=Solinas M, Thiriet N, El Rawas R, Lardeux V, Jaber M | title = Environmental enrichment during early stages of life reduces the behavioral, neurochemical, and molecular effects of cocaine | journal = Neuropsychopharmacology | volume = 34 | issue = 5 | pages = 1102\u201311 |date=April 2009 | pmid = 18463628 | doi = 10.1038/npp.2008.51 }}</ref> It was thus concluded that both the activating and rewarding effects are suppressed by environmental enrichment and early exposure to environmental enrichment can help prevent [[drug addiction]].<ref name = Solinas/>\n\n== Humans ==\n\nThough environmental enrichment research has been mostly done upon rodents, similar effects occur in primates,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kozorovitskiy Y, Gross CG, Kopil C | title = Experience induces structural and biochemical changes in the adult primate brain | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 102 | issue = 48 | pages = 17478\u201382 |date=November 2005 | pmid = 16299105 | pmc = 1297690 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0508817102 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> and are likely to affect the human brain. However, direct research upon human synapses and their numbers is limited since this requires [[histological]] study of the brain. A link, however, has been found between educational level and greater dendritic branch complexity following autopsy removal of the brain.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Jacobs B, Schall M, Scheibel AB | title = A quantitative dendritic analysis of Wernicke's area in humans. II. Gender, hemispheric, and environmental factors | journal = J. Comp. Neurol. | volume = 327 | issue = 1 | pages = 97\u2013111 |date=January 1993 | pmid = 8432910 | doi = 10.1002/cne.903270108 }}</ref>\n\n=== Localized cerebral cortex changes ===\nMRI detects localized [[cerebral cortex]] expansion after people learn complex tasks such as mirror reading (in this case in the right [[occipital cortex]]),<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ilg R, Wohlschl\u00e4ger AM, Gaser C | title = Gray matter increase induced by practice correlates with task-specific activation: a combined functional and morphometric magnetic resonance imaging study | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 28 | issue = 16 | pages = 4210\u20135 |date=April 2008 | pmid = 18417700 | pmc = 6670304 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.5722-07.2008 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> three-ball juggling (bilateral mid-[[Temporal lobe|temporal]] area and left posterior [[intraparietal sulcus]]),<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Draganski B, Gaser C, Busch V, Schuierer G, Bogdahn U, May A | title = Neuroplasticity: changes in grey matter induced by training | journal = Nature | volume = 427 | issue = 6972 | pages = 311\u20132 |date=January 2004 | pmid = 14737157 | doi = 10.1038/427311a }}</ref> and when medical students intensively revise for exams (bilaterally in the posterior and lateral [[parietal cortex]]).<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Draganski B, Gaser C, Kempermann G | title = Temporal and spatial dynamics of brain structure changes during extensive learning | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 26 | issue = 23 | pages = 6314\u20137 |date=June 2006 | pmid = 16763039 | pmc = 6675198 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4628-05.2006 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> Such changes in gray matter volume can be expected to link to changes in synapse numbers due to the increased numbers of glial cells and the expanded capillary vascularization needed to support their increased energy consumption.\n\n=== Institutional deprivation ===\nChildren that receive impoverished stimulation due to being confined to cots without social interaction or reliable caretakers in low quality [[orphanages]] show severe delays in cognitive and social development.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7610.1994.tb01220.x |vauthors=Kaler SR, Freeman BJ | title = Analysis of environmental deprivation: cognitive and social development in Romanian orphans | journal = J Child Psychol Psychiatry | volume = 35 | issue = 4 | pages = 769\u201381 |date=May 1994 | pmid = 7518826 }}</ref> 12% of them if adopted after 6 months of age show autistic or mildly autistic traits later at four years of age.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Rutter M, Andersen-Wood L, Beckett C | title = Quasi-autistic patterns following severe early global privation. English and Romanian Adoptees (ERA) Study Team | journal = J Child Psychol Psychiatry | volume = 40 | issue = 4 | pages = 537\u201349 |date=May 1999 | pmid = 10357161 | doi = 10.1017/S0021963099003935 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> Some children in such impoverished orphanages at two and half years of age still fail to produce intelligible words, though a year of foster care enabled such children to catch up in their language in most respects.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Windsor J, Glaze LE, Koga SF | title = Language acquisition with limited input: Romanian institution and foster care | journal = J. Speech Lang. Hear. Res. | volume = 50 | issue = 5 | pages = 1365\u201381 |date=October 2007 | pmid = 17905917 | doi = 10.1044/1092-4388(2007/095) }}</ref> Catch-up in other cognitive functioning also occurs after adoption, though problems continue in many children if this happens after the age of 6 months<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Beckett C, Maughan B, Rutter M | title = Do the effects of early severe deprivation on cognition persist into early adolescence? Findings from the English and Romanian adoptees study | journal = Child Dev | volume = 77 | issue = 3 | pages = 696\u2013711 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16686796 | doi = 10.1111/j.1467-8624.2006.00898.x |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\nSuch children show marked differences in their brains, consistent with research upon experiment animals, compared to children from normally stimulating environments. They have reduced brain activity in the [[Orbitofrontal cortex|orbital prefrontal cortex]], [[amygdala]], [[hippocampus]], [[temporal cortex]], and [[brain stem]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Chugani HT, Behen ME, Muzik O, Juh\u00e1sz C, Nagy F, Chugani DC | title = Local brain functional activity following early deprivation: a study of postinstitutionalized Romanian orphans | journal = NeuroImage | volume = 14 | issue = 6 | pages = 1290\u2013301 |date=December 2001 | pmid = 11707085 | doi = 10.1006/nimg.2001.0917 }}</ref> They also showed less developed [[white matter]] connections between different areas in their cerebral cortices, particularly the [[uncinate fasciculus]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Eluvathingal TJ, Chugani HT, Behen ME | title = Abnormal brain connectivity in children after early severe socioemotional deprivation: a diffusion tensor imaging study | journal = Pediatrics | volume = 117 | issue = 6 | pages = 2093\u2013100 |date=June 2006 | pmid = 16740852 | doi = 10.1542/peds.2005-1727 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\nConversely, enriching the experience of [[Premature birth|preterm infants]] with [[massage]] quickens the maturating of their [[EEG|electroencephalographic]] activity and their [[visual acuity]]. Moreover, as with enrichment in experimental animals, this associates with an increase in [[IGF-1]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Guzzetta A, Baldini S, Bancale A | title = Massage accelerates brain development and the maturation of visual function | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 29 | issue = 18 | pages = 6042\u201351 |date=May 2009 | pmid = 19420271 | pmc = 6665233 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.5548-08.2009 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n=== Cognitive reserve and resilience ===\nAnother source of evidence for the effect of environment stimulation upon the human brain is [[cognitive reserve]] (a measure of the brain\u2019s resilience to cognitive impairment) and the level of a person\u2019s education. Not only is higher education linked to a more cognitively demanding educational experience, but it also correlates with a person\u2019s general engagement in cognitively demanding activities.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1076/jcen.25.5.634.14572 |vauthors=Wilson R, Barnes L, Bennett D | title = Assessment of lifetime participation in cognitively stimulating activities | journal = J Clin Exp Neuropsychol | volume = 25 | issue = 5 | pages = 634\u201342 |date=August 2003 | pmid = 12815501 }}</ref> The more education a person has received, the less the effects of aging,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Corral M, Rodr\u00edguez M, Amenedo E, S\u00e1nchez JL, D\u00edaz F | title = Cognitive reserve, age, and neuropsychological performance in healthy participants | journal = Dev Neuropsychol | volume = 29 | issue = 3 | pages = 479\u201391 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16671863 | doi = 10.1207/s15326942dn2903_6 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Fritsch T, McClendon MJ, Smyth KA, Lerner AJ, Friedland RP, Larsen JD | title = Cognitive functioning in healthy aging: the role of reserve and lifestyle factors early in life | journal = Gerontologist | volume = 47 | issue = 3 | pages = 307\u201322 |date=June 2007 | pmid = 17565095 | doi = 10.1093/geront/47.3.307 }}</ref> dementia,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Hall CB, Derby C, LeValley A, Katz MJ, Verghese J, Lipton RB | title = Education delays accelerated decline on a memory test in persons who develop dementia | journal = Neurology | volume = 69 | issue = 17 | pages = 1657\u201364 |date=October 2007 | pmid = 17954781 | doi = 10.1212/01.wnl.0000278163.82636.30 }}</ref> white matter hyperintensities,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Nebes RD, Meltzer CC, Whyte EM | title = The relation of white matter hyperintensities to cognitive performance in the normal old: education matters | journal = Neuropsychol Dev Cogn B Aging Neuropsychol Cogn | volume = 13 | issue = 3\u20134 | pages = 326\u201340 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16887777 | doi = 10.1080/138255890969294 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> MRI-defined brain infarcts,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Elkins JS, Longstreth WT, Manolio TA, Newman AB, Bhadelia RA, Johnston SC | title = Education and the cognitive decline associated with MRI-defined brain infarct | journal = Neurology | volume = 67 | issue = 3 | pages = 435\u201340 |date=August 2006 | pmid = 16894104 | doi = 10.1212/01.wnl.0000228246.89109.98 }}</ref> Alzheimer's disease,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Koepsell TD, Kurland BF, Harel O, Johnson EA, Zhou XH, Kukull WA | title = Education, cognitive function, and severity of neuropathology in Alzheimer disease | journal = Neurology | volume = 70 | issue = 19 Pt 2 | pages = 1732\u20139 |date=May 2008 | pmid = 18160675 | doi = 10.1212/01.wnl.0000284603.85621.aa }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Roe CM, Mintun MA, D'Angelo G, Xiong C, Grant EA, Morris JC | title = Alzheimer's and Cognitive Reserve: Education Effect Varies with 11CPIB Uptake | journal = Arch. Neurol. | volume = 65 | issue = 11 | pages = 1467\u201371 |date=November 2008 | pmid = 19001165 | pmc = 2752218 | doi = 10.1001/archneur.65.11.1467  }}</ref> and traumatic brain injury.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1207/S15324826AN1003_04 |vauthors=Kesler SR, Adams HF, Blasey CM, Bigler ED | title = Premorbid intellectual functioning, education, and brain size in traumatic brain injury: an investigation of the cognitive reserve hypothesis | journal = Appl Neuropsychol | volume = 10 | issue = 3 | pages = 153\u201362 | year = 2003 | pmid = 12890641 }}</ref> Also, aging and dementia are less in those that engage in complex cognitive tasks.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Fratiglioni L, Paillard-Borg S, Winblad B | title = An active and socially integrated lifestyle in late life might protect against dementia | journal = Lancet Neurol | volume = 3 | issue = 6 | pages = 343\u201353 |date=June 2004 | pmid = 15157849 | doi = 10.1016/S1474-4422(04)00767-7 }}</ref> The cognitive decline of those with epilepsy could also be affected by the level of a person\u2019s education.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Pai MC, Tsai JJ | title = Is cognitive reserve applicable to epilepsy? The effect of educational level on the cognitive decline after onset of epilepsy | journal = Epilepsia | volume = 46 | issue = Suppl 1 | pages = 7\u201310 | year = 2005 | pmid = 15816971 | doi = 10.1111/j.0013-9580.2005.461003.x }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{col div|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Behavioral enrichment]]\n* [[Neural development]]\n* [[Neuroplasticity]]\n* [[Perceptual learning]]\n* [[Phenotypic plasticity]]\n* [[Rat Park]]\n* [[Stimulation]]\n* [[Synaptogenesis]]\n{{colend}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book | author = Diamond, Marian Cleeves | title = Enriching Heredity: The Impact of the Environment on the Anatomy of the Brain | publisher = Free Press | location = New York | year = 1988 | isbn = 978-0-02-907431-2 | author-link = Marian Diamond }}\n* {{cite book | author = Jensen, Eric | title = Enriching the Brain: How to maximize every learner's potential | publisher = Jossey-Bass, A John Wiley & Sons Imprint | location = San Francisco | year = 2006 | isbn = 978-0-7879-7547-0 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/enrichingbrainho00jens }}\n* {{cite book | vauthors = Renner MJ, Rosenzweig MR | title = Enriched and Impoverished Environments: Effects on Brain and Behavior | publisher = Springer-Verlag | location = New York | year = 1987 | isbn = 978-3-540-96523-7 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.newhorizons.org/neuro/diamond_enrich.htm The Significance of Enrichment]\n\n[[Category:Behavioral neuroscience]]\n[[Category:Cognitive neuroscience]]\n[[Category:Developmental biology]]\n[[Category:Developmental neuroscience]]\n[[Category:Developmental psychology]]\n[[Category:Educational psychology]]\n[[Category:Human development]]\n[[Category:Learning]]\n[[Category:Neurophysiology]]\n[[Category:Neuropsychology]]\n[[Category:Personal development]]\n[[Category:Rehabilitation medicine]]\n[[Category:Developmental psychiatry]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCognitive reserve and resilience:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environmental_enrichment"}
{"title_page": "M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n[[File:M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder-040305.jpg|thumb|Slotsgaden (''The Castle Street)]]\n[[File:M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder-church-040305.jpg|thumb|M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder Church]]\n[[File:M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder alley.JPG|thumb|Alley]]\n\n'''M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8m\u00f8\u02c0jl\u0329\u02ccts\u02b0\u00f8n\u02c0\u0250}}) is a small town in Denmark, located in M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder Parish and [[T\u00f8nder Municipality]] in the southwestern corner of the [[Denmark|Danish]] peninsula of [[Jutland]] 5 kilometers north of the Danish-German border and 4 kilometer west of [[T\u00f8nder]].\n\nIt has a population of 842 (1 January 2019),<ref>[https://m.statbank.dk/TableInfo/BY3?lang=en BY3: Population 1st January, by urban areas] The Mobile Statbank from [[Statistics Denmark]]</ref> \n\nM\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder is known for the royal residence of [[Schackenborg Castle]] which was the home of the Danish [[Queen Margrethe II]] and Prince Henrik's younger son Prince Joachim until 2014. Prince Joachim and his second wife Princess Marie married at M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder church on May 24th 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=HRH PRINCE JOACHIM & HRH PRINCESS MARIE|url=http://kongehuset.dk/Den-kongelige-familie/Prins-Joachim-og-Prinsesse-Marie|publisher=Royal Family of Denmark}}</ref>\n\nM\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder Church is one of the largest village churches in the southern Jutland and has a rich interior e.g. a painting of the [[Golden Horns of Gallehus]] discovered at Gallehus just north of the town.\n\nM\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder is also known for the main street \"Slotsgaden\" (The Castle Street) covered with paving-stones and flanked with lime trees.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Coord|54.94470|N|8.80056|E|display=title|region:DK_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mogeltonder}}\n[[Category:Cities and towns in the Region of Southern Denmark]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n[[File:M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder-040305.jpg|thumb|Slotsgaden (''The Castle Street)]]\n[[File:M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder-church-040305.jpg|thumb|M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder Church]]\n[[File:M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder alley.JPG|thumb|Alley]]\n\n'''M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8m\u00f8\u02c0l\u0329\u02ccts\u02b0\u00f8n\u02c0\u0250}}) is a small town in Denmark, located in M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder Parish and [[T\u00f8nder Municipality]] in the southwestern corner of the [[Denmark|Danish]] peninsula of [[Jutland]] 5 kilometers north of the Danish-German border and 4 kilometer west of [[T\u00f8nder]].\n\nIt has a population of 842 (1 January 2019),<ref>[https://m.statbank.dk/TableInfo/BY3?lang=en BY3: Population 1st January, by urban areas] The Mobile Statbank from [[Statistics Denmark]]</ref> \n\nM\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder is known for the royal residence of [[Schackenborg Castle]] which was the home of the Danish [[Queen Margrethe II]] and Prince Henrik's younger son Prince Joachim until 2014. Prince Joachim and his second wife Princess Marie married at M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder church on May 24th 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=HRH PRINCE JOACHIM & HRH PRINCESS MARIE|url=http://kongehuset.dk/Den-kongelige-familie/Prins-Joachim-og-Prinsesse-Marie|publisher=Royal Family of Denmark}}</ref>\n\nM\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder Church is one of the largest village churches in the southern Jutland and has a rich interior e.g. a painting of the [[Golden Horns of Gallehus]] discovered at Gallehus just north of the town.\n\nM\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder is also known for the main street \"Slotsgaden\" (The Castle Street) covered with paving-stones and flanked with lime trees.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Coord|54.94470|N|8.80056|E|display=title|region:DK_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mogeltonder}}\n[[Category:Cities and towns in the Region of Southern Denmark]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%B8gelt%C3%B8nder"}
{"title_page": "Peter V'landys", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n'''Peter V'landys''' is an Australian [[horse racing]] administrator. He is the [[Chief executive officer|chief executive]] and a board member of Racing [[New South Wales]] (Racing NSW) as well as the chairman of the [[Australian Rugby League Commission]].Who has no idea about what the people want he only cares about noneuy\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nV'landys grew up in [[Wollongong]] where he attended Keira Boys High School before graduating in 1984 from the [[University of Wollongong]]\nwith a Bachelor of Commerce degree, majoring in [[Accounting|accountancy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uow.edu.au/alumni/alumnistories/UOW097305.html |title=Alumni Profiles \u2013 Commerce |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518072923/https://www.uow.edu.au/alumni/alumnistories/UOW097305.html |archivedate=18 May 2015 |website=University of Wollongong |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/running-hard-on-the-peoples-diet-20120622-20tun.html |title=Running hard on the people's diet |last=Presnell |first=Max |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=23 June 2012 |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"kythera-family-bio\">{{cite web |author=Kytherian Newsletter Sydney |url=http://www.kythera-family.net/index.php?nav=3-10&did=22219 |title=Detailed Biography |publisher=kythera-family.net |date=14 April 2014 |accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref>  He is of [[Greeks|Greek]] heritage from [[Kythira]]; the name \"V'landys\" is the [[Anglicization|Anglicized]] form of the Greek surname \"Vlandis\".<ref name=\"kythera-family-bio\"/>\n\n== Racing administration ==\n\nV'landys became involved in racing administration in 1988 when he was appointed chief executive of the [[New South Wales]] (NSW) Harness Racing Club. Under his administration, the NSW Harness Racing Club established several commercial enterprises that provided it with the broadest revenue base of any racing club in [[Australia]].\n\nDuring this period V'landys also played a role in negotiating the $1&nbsp;billion privatisation of the NSW [[Totalisator Agency Board|TAB]] and the restructuring of the racing industry's finances.\n\nIn 2004 he was appointed chief executive and board member of [[Racing NSW]]. In this role V'landys also sits as a board member of several other NSW and Australian racing and wagering industry boards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.racingnsw.com.au/about-us-contacts/board-members/ |title=Board Members |website=Racing New South Wales |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Equine influenza outbreak ===\n\nIn mid-2007, the racing industry was brought to a standstill as a result of an outbreak of [[Equine influenza|equine influenza]].  [[New South Wales]] was the worst affected state with all racing cancelled and the movement of all horses prohibited indefinitely.\n\nV'landys assumed responsibility for the overall co-ordination of the industry's response to this crisis, and developed and implemented contingency plans to counter the effects of the outbreak, including negotiating a $235&nbsp;million rescue package.\n\nHe also lobbied [[Government of New South Wales|NSW ministers]] for the provision of further financial assistance which resulted in the provision of a $7.5&nbsp;million grants scheme and the establishment of a special mortgage deferment scheme and a further one-off grant to help promote the industry following the resumption of normal racing activities.<ref name=\"theaustralian\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/turf-thoroughbreds/racing-nsw-chief-peter-vlandys-is-poised-for-big-fight-with-nsw-treasury/story-fnajufri-1226315910856 |title=Racing NSW chief Peter V'landys is poised for the big fight with NSW Treasury |date=2 April 2012 |last=Cormick |first=Brendan |work=[[The Australian]]}}</ref>\n\n=== World Youth Day negotiations ===\n\nFollowing the government's announcement that the [[World Youth Day 2008]] would be held in Sydney and centred at [[Randwick Racecourse]], V'landys coordinated the industry's planning for the use of the racecourse and the disruption which would be caused to the racing industry.  This included negotiating a $40&nbsp;million compensation package for the racing industry.<ref name=\"theaustralian\" />\n\n=== Race field legislation ===\n\nV'landys in 2008 was responsible for enforcing corporate bookmakers and other wagering operators to pay racing for the use of its product. Up until then the bookmakers paid very little and determined themselves how much to pay.\nAfter first looking at enforcing copyright led V\u2019landys to Race Field legislation.\nThe bookmakers challenged Racing NSW all the way to the high court.\nThe High Court found in favour of Racing NSW in a unanimous decision.\nThe win meant racing would earn over a billion dollars in the next ten years.\nIt also meant that sport could also charge the Bookmakers for the use of its product making millions of dollars for sport.\n.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/horseracing/racings-100m-windfall-after-court-ruling-20120330-1w22x.html |title=Racing's $100m windfall after court ruling |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=30 March 2012 |last=Young |first=Craig |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/archive/national-old/better-betting-deal-is-a-big-win-for-all-sport/story-e6freuzr-1226314944905 |title=Better betting Deal is a big win for all sport |last=Tabakov |first=Nick |date=31 March 2012 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Presnell |first=Max |url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/horseracing/vlandys-leads-way-others-must-follow-20120330-1w3lt.html |title=V'landys leads way, others must follow |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=31 March 2012 |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/superracing/let-the-money-flow/story-fn67r1j3-1226315064092 |title=Let the money flow |last=Thomas |first=Ray |date=31 March 2012 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph (Australia)]] |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Clinton |url=http://www.racenet.com.au/news/78742/V%E2%80%99landys-%E2%80%93-%E2%80%98the-bloke-that-saved-the-industry%E2%80%99 |title=V'landys \u2013 'the bloke that saved the industry' |publisher=Racenet.com.au |date=30 March 2013|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Trackside'' ===\n\nIn 2010 V'Landys negotiated the sale to [[Tabcorp Holdings|Tabcorp]] of the Racing NSW future revenues from the ''Trackside'' computer racing game.  This sale realised $150&nbsp;million and allowed the development of new spectator facilities at the [[Randwick Racecourse]].<ref>{{cite news ||last=Carson |first=Vanda |url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/tabcorp-to-pay-150m-for-facelift-at-randwick-20101006-167x0.html |title=TabCorp to pay $150m for facelift at Randwick |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=7 October 2010 |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Recognition ===\n\nIn 2013 he was ranked with John Messara as the 40th of Sydney's most influential people<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/image-gallery/ad65cd48ebc6e6d8bf3364e41d04837e |title=Sydney's 50 most powerful people |date=3 March 2013 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Sunday Telegraph (Australia)]] |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref> and [[The Australian]] ranked him 22nd of the top 50 people in Australian sport.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/top50/2013/sport |title=Top 50 Sports People |date=5 May 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130505061603/www.theaustralian.com.au/top50/2013/sport |archivedate=5 May 2013 |work=[[The Australian]] |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the Sydney Daily Telegraph ranked V'Landys 6th from among a list of 100 of Sydney\u2019s most powerful and influential people. <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=DTWEB_WRE170_a_GGL&dest=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/the-sydney-power-100-the-100-most-powerful-people-in-sydney-10081/news-story/c7891fd43ab7e7c70d9dd3f597490ac4&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium |title=Sydney's 100 most powerfull people. |date=28 February 2019 |work=[[dailytelegraph.com.au]] |access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nV'Landys was awarded Member of the [[Order of Australia]] in the [[2014 Australia Day Honours]] for service to horse racing.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/peter-vlandys-awarded-member-of-the-order-for-services-to-racing-dedicates-the-honour-to-his-parents/story-fni0cx12-1226810631502 |title=Peter V'landys, awarded Member of the Order for services to racing, dedicates the honour to his parents |last=Lehmann |first=John |date=23 January 2014 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Sunday Telegraph (Australia)]] |accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Tax parity ===\n\nIn 2015, along with John Messara, V\u2019Landys negotiated with the [[Government of New South Wales|NSW state government]] for the introduction of legislation to reduce the rate of government tax on [[Tote board|totalisator]] and [[Fixed-odds betting|fixed-odds betting]] through [[Tabcorp Holdings|Tabcorp]] to bring it into line with the rate of tax paid in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].\n\n=== The Everest race===\n\nIn February 2017, V'Landys devised a new race called the [[The Everest|Everest]], which was to be conducted over 1200 metres and carry [[Purse distribution|prize money]] of $10 million, making it the richest race in Australia and in the world on turf. The inaugural Everest race was run at [[Randwick Racecourse]] on 14 October 2017. It attracted a record crowd to Randwick Racecourse as well as record betting on an NSW race.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/the-everest-bold-and-brash-race-put-sydney-back-on-the-map/news-story/f560d1f362978f147e849d052d9ae794 |title=The Everest: \u2018Bold and brash\u2019 race put Sydney back on the map |date=16 October 2017 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph (Australia)]] |accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/superracing/speed-thrill-everest-moves-on-next-generation-audience/news-story/2b623c85455a3ab914f0459d7d3cc566 |title=Speed thrill Everest moves on next generation audience |last=Thomas |first=Ray |date=15 October 2017 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph (Australia)]] |accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn conjunction with the second running of the Everest, V'Landys also devised and implemented another new and unique race, The Kosciusko, which was specifically directed towards country trained horses and carried prizemoney of $1.3 million making it the world\u2019s richest country race.\n\nPrior to the 2018 event, the race attracted criticism<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.9news.com.au/2018/10/09/15/07/opera-house-everest-projection-brand-critic-racing-nsw-berejiklian |title=Opera House brand guru delivers Everest-sized slap in face to Racing NSW |last=Saunokonoko |first=Mark |date=9 October 2018 |work=[[Nine News]] |access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/sydney-opera-house-action-to-deflect-everest-light-show-20181008-p508f2.html |title=Sydney Opera House 'action' to deflect Everest light show |last=Pitt |first=Helen |date=9 October 2018 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |language=en |access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref> from the Australian public and media after organisers of the event successfully lobbied for the sails of the [[UNESCO world heritage]] [[Sydney Opera House]] to be used as an advertisement for the race. Public backlash and protests against this proposal and government support of it were held at the Opera House along with submission of a petition with over 300,000 signatures collected in less than a week in October 2018, but the pre-race event went ahead in a modified format<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.news.com.au/national/nsw-act/news/opera-house-light-display-dividing-sydney-will-last-just-six-minutes/news-story/8d48d4150caa93893a1ea7a898f7b05e |title=How the Everest Opera House showdown will play out |date=9 October 2018 |work=[[news.com.au]] |access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref>.\n\n=== Australian Rugby League Commission===\nOn 13 March 2018, V'Landys was appointed as an independent board member of the ARL Commission in the first step to constitutional reform in the sport of Rugby League.  The ARL Commission also conducts the NRL competition and V'Landys appointment received the unanimous support of the 16 clubs in that competition.<ref> | url=https://www.nrl.com/about-us/ </ref>.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.racingnsw.com.au/ Racing NSW website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vlandys, Peter}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:People from Wollongong]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian sports executives and administrators]]\n[[Category:University of Wollongong alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n'''Peter V'landys''' is an Australian [[horse racing]] administrator. He is the [[Chief executive officer|chief executive]] and a board member of Racing [[New South Wales]] (Racing NSW) as well as the chairman of the [[Australian Rugby League Commission]].\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nV'landys grew up in [[Wollongong]] where he attended Keira Boys High School before graduating in 1984 from the [[University of Wollongong]]\nwith a Bachelor of Commerce degree, majoring in [[Accounting|accountancy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uow.edu.au/alumni/alumnistories/UOW097305.html |title=Alumni Profiles \u2013 Commerce |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518072923/https://www.uow.edu.au/alumni/alumnistories/UOW097305.html |archivedate=18 May 2015 |website=University of Wollongong |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/running-hard-on-the-peoples-diet-20120622-20tun.html |title=Running hard on the people's diet |last=Presnell |first=Max |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=23 June 2012 |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"kythera-family-bio\">{{cite web |author=Kytherian Newsletter Sydney |url=http://www.kythera-family.net/index.php?nav=3-10&did=22219 |title=Detailed Biography |publisher=kythera-family.net |date=14 April 2014 |accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref>  He is of [[Greeks|Greek]] heritage from [[Kythira]]; the name \"V'landys\" is the [[Anglicization|Anglicized]] form of the Greek surname \"Vlandis\".<ref name=\"kythera-family-bio\"/>\n\n== Racing administration ==\n\nV'landys became involved in racing administration in 1988 when he was appointed chief executive of the [[New South Wales]] (NSW) Harness Racing Club. Under his administration, the NSW Harness Racing Club established several commercial enterprises that provided it with the broadest revenue base of any racing club in [[Australia]].\n\nDuring this period V'landys also played a role in negotiating the $1&nbsp;billion privatisation of the NSW [[Totalisator Agency Board|TAB]] and the restructuring of the racing industry's finances.\n\nIn 2004 he was appointed chief executive and board member of [[Racing NSW]]. In this role V'landys also sits as a board member of several other NSW and Australian racing and wagering industry boards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.racingnsw.com.au/about-us-contacts/board-members/ |title=Board Members |website=Racing New South Wales |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Equine influenza outbreak ===\n\nIn mid-2007, the racing industry was brought to a standstill as a result of an outbreak of [[Equine influenza|equine influenza]].  [[New South Wales]] was the worst affected state with all racing cancelled and the movement of all horses prohibited indefinitely.\n\nV'landys assumed responsibility for the overall co-ordination of the industry's response to this crisis, and developed and implemented contingency plans to counter the effects of the outbreak, including negotiating a $235&nbsp;million rescue package.\n\nHe also lobbied [[Government of New South Wales|NSW ministers]] for the provision of further financial assistance which resulted in the provision of a $7.5&nbsp;million grants scheme and the establishment of a special mortgage deferment scheme and a further one-off grant to help promote the industry following the resumption of normal racing activities.<ref name=\"theaustralian\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/turf-thoroughbreds/racing-nsw-chief-peter-vlandys-is-poised-for-big-fight-with-nsw-treasury/story-fnajufri-1226315910856 |title=Racing NSW chief Peter V'landys is poised for the big fight with NSW Treasury |date=2 April 2012 |last=Cormick |first=Brendan |work=[[The Australian]]}}</ref>\n\n=== World Youth Day negotiations ===\n\nFollowing the government's announcement that the [[World Youth Day 2008]] would be held in Sydney and centred at [[Randwick Racecourse]], V'landys coordinated the industry's planning for the use of the racecourse and the disruption which would be caused to the racing industry.  This included negotiating a $40&nbsp;million compensation package for the racing industry.<ref name=\"theaustralian\" />\n\n=== Race field legislation ===\n\nV'landys in 2008 was responsible for enforcing corporate bookmakers and other wagering operators to pay racing for the use of its product. Up until then the bookmakers paid very little and determined themselves how much to pay.\nAfter first looking at enforcing copyright led V\u2019landys to Race Field legislation.\nThe bookmakers challenged Racing NSW all the way to the high court.\nThe High Court found in favour of Racing NSW in a unanimous decision.\nThe win meant racing would earn over a billion dollars in the next ten years.\nIt also meant that sport could also charge the Bookmakers for the use of its product making millions of dollars for sport.\n.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/horseracing/racings-100m-windfall-after-court-ruling-20120330-1w22x.html |title=Racing's $100m windfall after court ruling |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=30 March 2012 |last=Young |first=Craig |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/archive/national-old/better-betting-deal-is-a-big-win-for-all-sport/story-e6freuzr-1226314944905 |title=Better betting Deal is a big win for all sport |last=Tabakov |first=Nick |date=31 March 2012 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Presnell |first=Max |url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/horseracing/vlandys-leads-way-others-must-follow-20120330-1w3lt.html |title=V'landys leads way, others must follow |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=31 March 2012 |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/superracing/let-the-money-flow/story-fn67r1j3-1226315064092 |title=Let the money flow |last=Thomas |first=Ray |date=31 March 2012 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph (Australia)]] |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Clinton |url=http://www.racenet.com.au/news/78742/V%E2%80%99landys-%E2%80%93-%E2%80%98the-bloke-that-saved-the-industry%E2%80%99 |title=V'landys \u2013 'the bloke that saved the industry' |publisher=Racenet.com.au |date=30 March 2013|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Trackside'' ===\n\nIn 2010 V'Landys negotiated the sale to [[Tabcorp Holdings|Tabcorp]] of the Racing NSW future revenues from the ''Trackside'' computer racing game.  This sale realised $150&nbsp;million and allowed the development of new spectator facilities at the [[Randwick Racecourse]].<ref>{{cite news ||last=Carson |first=Vanda |url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/tabcorp-to-pay-150m-for-facelift-at-randwick-20101006-167x0.html |title=TabCorp to pay $150m for facelift at Randwick |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=7 October 2010 |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Recognition ===\n\nIn 2013 he was ranked with John Messara as the 40th of Sydney's most influential people<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/image-gallery/ad65cd48ebc6e6d8bf3364e41d04837e |title=Sydney's 50 most powerful people |date=3 March 2013 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Sunday Telegraph (Australia)]] |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref> and [[The Australian]] ranked him 22nd of the top 50 people in Australian sport.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/top50/2013/sport |title=Top 50 Sports People |date=5 May 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130505061603/www.theaustralian.com.au/top50/2013/sport |archivedate=5 May 2013 |work=[[The Australian]] |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the Sydney Daily Telegraph ranked V'Landys 6th from among a list of 100 of Sydney\u2019s most powerful and influential people. <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=DTWEB_WRE170_a_GGL&dest=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/the-sydney-power-100-the-100-most-powerful-people-in-sydney-10081/news-story/c7891fd43ab7e7c70d9dd3f597490ac4&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium |title=Sydney's 100 most powerfull people. |date=28 February 2019 |work=[[dailytelegraph.com.au]] |access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nV'Landys was awarded Member of the [[Order of Australia]] in the [[2014 Australia Day Honours]] for service to horse racing.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/peter-vlandys-awarded-member-of-the-order-for-services-to-racing-dedicates-the-honour-to-his-parents/story-fni0cx12-1226810631502 |title=Peter V'landys, awarded Member of the Order for services to racing, dedicates the honour to his parents |last=Lehmann |first=John |date=23 January 2014 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Sunday Telegraph (Australia)]] |accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Tax parity ===\n\nIn 2015, along with John Messara, V\u2019Landys negotiated with the [[Government of New South Wales|NSW state government]] for the introduction of legislation to reduce the rate of government tax on [[Tote board|totalisator]] and [[Fixed-odds betting|fixed-odds betting]] through [[Tabcorp Holdings|Tabcorp]] to bring it into line with the rate of tax paid in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].\n\n=== The Everest race===\n\nIn February 2017, V'Landys devised a new race called the [[The Everest|Everest]], which was to be conducted over 1200 metres and carry [[Purse distribution|prize money]] of $10 million, making it the richest race in Australia and in the world on turf. The inaugural Everest race was run at [[Randwick Racecourse]] on 14 October 2017. It attracted a record crowd to Randwick Racecourse as well as record betting on an NSW race.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/the-everest-bold-and-brash-race-put-sydney-back-on-the-map/news-story/f560d1f362978f147e849d052d9ae794 |title=The Everest: \u2018Bold and brash\u2019 race put Sydney back on the map |date=16 October 2017 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph (Australia)]] |accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/superracing/speed-thrill-everest-moves-on-next-generation-audience/news-story/2b623c85455a3ab914f0459d7d3cc566 |title=Speed thrill Everest moves on next generation audience |last=Thomas |first=Ray |date=15 October 2017 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph (Australia)]] |accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn conjunction with the second running of the Everest, V'Landys also devised and implemented another new and unique race, The Kosciusko, which was specifically directed towards country trained horses and carried prizemoney of $1.3 million making it the world\u2019s richest country race.\n\nPrior to the 2018 event, the race attracted criticism<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.9news.com.au/2018/10/09/15/07/opera-house-everest-projection-brand-critic-racing-nsw-berejiklian |title=Opera House brand guru delivers Everest-sized slap in face to Racing NSW |last=Saunokonoko |first=Mark |date=9 October 2018 |work=[[Nine News]] |access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/sydney-opera-house-action-to-deflect-everest-light-show-20181008-p508f2.html |title=Sydney Opera House 'action' to deflect Everest light show |last=Pitt |first=Helen |date=9 October 2018 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |language=en |access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref> from the Australian public and media after organisers of the event successfully lobbied for the sails of the [[UNESCO world heritage]] [[Sydney Opera House]] to be used as an advertisement for the race. Public backlash and protests against this proposal and government support of it were held at the Opera House along with submission of a petition with over 300,000 signatures collected in less than a week in October 2018, but the pre-race event went ahead in a modified format<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.news.com.au/national/nsw-act/news/opera-house-light-display-dividing-sydney-will-last-just-six-minutes/news-story/8d48d4150caa93893a1ea7a898f7b05e |title=How the Everest Opera House showdown will play out |date=9 October 2018 |work=[[news.com.au]] |access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref>.\n\n=== Australian Rugby League Commission===\nOn 13 March 2018, V'Landys was appointed as an independent board member of the ARL Commission in the first step to constitutional reform in the sport of Rugby League.  The ARL Commission also conducts the NRL competition and V'Landys appointment received the unanimous support of the 16 clubs in that competition.<ref> | url=https://www.nrl.com/about-us/ </ref>.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.racingnsw.com.au/ Racing NSW website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vlandys, Peter}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:People from Wollongong]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian sports executives and administrators]]\n[[Category:University of Wollongong alumni]]\n", "name_user": "14.203.224.59", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_V%27landys"}
{"title_page": "Sumberawan", "text_new": "{{Short description|Buddhist stupa near Malang, East Java, Indonesia}}\n{{Infobox Historic building\n|image=047 View from East, Candi Sumberawan (39521127305).jpg\n|caption=Sumberawan stupa viewed from east\n|name=Candi Sumberawan\n|map_type=\n|map_size=\n|latitude=\n|longitude=\n|location_town=[[Malang Regency|Malang]], [[East Java]]. \n|location_country=[[Indonesia]]\n|architect=\n|client=\n|engineer=\n|construction_start_date=  \n|completion_date=  \n|date_demolished=\n|cost=\n|structural_system= \n|style=[[Candi of Indonesia|Candi]] [[stupa]] \n|size= 6.25 m x 6.25 m x 5.23 m\n| coordinates = {{coord|7|51|25|S|112|39|7.2|E|source:frwiki_region:ID|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Sumberawan''' is a [[Buddhist]] [[stupa]] located in Toyomarto village, Sumberawan subdistrict, [[Malang Regency]], [[East Java]], [[Indonesia]]. The stupa is located on the highlands, on the southern slope of [[Mount Arjuno]], and located about 6 kilometres north from [[Singhasari temple]], therefore, the stupa is traditionally linked to the historic [[Singhasari]] Kingdom circa 13th Century CE. The experts however, suggest that the stupa structure is dated from around 14th to 15th century CE, during Majapahit period.<ref name =\"BPCB-Jatim-Sumberawan\">{{Cite web |url=https://kebudayaan.kemdikbud.go.id/bpcbjatim/candi-sumberawan/ |title=Candi Sumberawan | date = 26 January 2015 |author = Balai Pelestarian Cagar Budaya Jawa Timur|work =Dirjen Kebudayaan, Kementerian Pendidikan dan Kebudayaan |language=id|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Location and architecture==\nSumberawan is quite unique, since it was the only Buddhist shrine in East Java that was built in the shape of [[stupa]] structure. In contrast to Buddhist temples in the region that built in typical [[Candi of Indonesia|candi]] architecture; such as nearby [[Singhasari temple|Singhasari]], [[Jago temple|Jago]], Brahu in [[Trowulan]] and [[Jabung]] temple in Paiton.\n\nThe stupa consists of square base and cylindrical body, while the pinnacle is missing. It is made of andesite stone with a length of 6.25 m, width of 6.25 m, and height of 5.23 mentres.\n\nBuilt at an altitude of 650 m above sea level, at the foot of Mount Arjuno, the scenery around this temple is quite beautiful. The temple is located near a [[Spring (hydrology)|water spring]] with a very clear water, thus gave the name of the temple; ''Sumber-awan'', in  [[Javanese language|Javanese]] ''sumber'' means \"water spring\", while ''awan'' means \"noon\".\n\n==See also ==\n{{Portal|Indonesia}}\n*[[Candi of Indonesia]]\n*[[Buddhism in Indonesia]]\n*[[Prajnaparamita of Java]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commons category|Candi Sumberawan}}\n\n{{Buddhist Temples in Indonesia}}\n{{Indonesia topics}}\n\n[[Category:Buddhist temples in Indonesia|Sumberawan]]\n[[Category:Cultural Properties of Indonesia in East Java]]\n[[Category:Singhasari]]\n[[Category:14th-century Buddhist temples]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Buddhist stupa near Malang, East Java, Indonesia}}\n{{Infobox Historic building\n|image=047 View from East, Candi Sumberawan (39521127305).jpg\n|caption=Sumberawan stupa viewed from east\n|name=Candi Sumberawan\n|map_type=\n|map_size=\n|latitude=\n|longitude=\n|location_town=[[Malang Regency|Malang]], [[East Java]]. \n|location_country=[[Indonesia]]\n|architect=\n|client=\n|engineer=\n|construction_start_date=  \n|completion_date=  \n|date_demolished=\n|cost=\n|structural_system= \n|style=[[Candi of Indonesia|Candi]] [[stupa]] \n|size= 6.25 m x 6.25 m x 5.23 m\n| coordinates = {{coord|7|51|25|S|112|39|7.2|E|source:frwiki_region:ID|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Sumberawan''' is a [[Buddhist]] [[stupa]] located in Toyomarto village, Sumberawan subdistrict, [[Malang Regency]], [[East Java]], [[Indonesia]]. The stupa is located on the highlands, on the southern slope of [[Mount Arjuno]], and located about 6 kilometres north from [[Singhasari temple]], therefore, the stupa is traditionally linked to the historic [[Singhasari]] Kingdom circa 13th Century CE. The experts however, suggest that the stupa structure is dated from around 14th to 15th century CE, during Majapahit period.<ref name =\"BPCB-Jatim-Sumberawan\">{{Cite web |url=https://kebudayaan.kemdikbud.go.id/bpcbjatim/candi-sumberawan/ |title=Candi Sumberawan | date = 26 January 2015 |author = Balai Pelestarian Cagar Budaya Jawa Timur|work =Dirjen Kebudayaan, Kementerian Pendidikan dan Kebudayaan |language=id|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Location and architecture==\nSumberawan is quite unique, since it was the only Buddhist shrine in East Java that was built in the shape of [[stupa]] structure. In contrast to Buddhist temples in the region that built in typical [[Candi of Indonesia|candi]] architecture; such as nearby [[Singhasari temple|Singhasari]], [[Jago temple|Jago]], Brahu in [[Trowulan]] and [[Jabung]] temple in Paiton. The stupa consists of square base and cylindrical body, while the pinnacle is missing. It is made of andesite stone with a length of 6.25 m, width of 6.25 m, and height of 5.23 mentres.\n\nBuilt at an altitude of 650 m above sea level, at the foot of Mount Arjuno, the scenery around this temple is quite beautiful. The temple is located near a [[Spring (hydrology)|water spring]] with a very clear water, thus gave the name of the temple; ''Sumber-awan'', in  [[Javanese language|Javanese]] ''sumber'' means \"water spring\", while ''awan'' means \"noon\".\n\n==See also ==\n{{Portal|Indonesia}}\n*[[Candi of Indonesia]]\n*[[Buddhism in Indonesia]]\n*[[Prajnaparamita of Java]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commons category|Candi Sumberawan}}\n\n{{Buddhist Temples in Indonesia}}\n{{Indonesia topics}}\n\n[[Category:Buddhist temples in Indonesia|Sumberawan]]\n[[Category:Cultural Properties of Indonesia in East Java]]\n[[Category:Singhasari]]\n[[Category:14th-century Buddhist temples]]\n", "name_user": "Gunkarta", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLocation and architecture", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sumberawan"}
{"title_page": "Science and technology in Jordan", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{tone|date=September 2017}}\n{{one source|date=September 2017}}\n}}\n\n'''[[Science]] and [[Technology]]''' is '''[[Jordan|Jordan's]]''' fastest-growing economic sector. This growth is occurring across multiple industries, including information and communications technology (ICTs), solar and wind energy and nuclear technology.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jcp-jordan.org/en/page/ict|title=ICT|work=jcp-jordan.org}}</ref><ref>[https://photos.state.gov/libraries/jordan/444376/pdf/2014CCGFinal.pdf Doing Business in Jordan: 2014 Country Commercial Guide for U.S. Companies]</ref>\n\n== Science policy framework ==\n\n=== Science, Technology and Innovation Policy and Strategy ===\nJordan's Higher Council for Science and Technology (est. 1987) is an independent public body that acts as a national umbrella organization for scientific research. It is the Higher Council for Science and Technology which drew up the first national policy for science and technology in 1995. In 2013, it completed the national ''Science, Technology and Innovation Policy and Strategy'' (2013\u20132017), which has seven broad objectives. These are to:<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0023/002354/235406e.pdf|title=UNESCO Science Report: towards 2030|last=|first=|publisher=UNESCO|year=2015|isbn=978-92-3-100129-1|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref>\n* incite the government and the scientific community to adopt the requisite research priorities to develop a knowledge economy, as identified by the Higher Council for Science and Technology and the Scientific Research Support Fund in 2010 in ''Defining Scientific Research Priorities in Jordan for the Years 2011\u20132020'';\n* generalize a science culture in the education system;\n* harness research to development;\n* build knowledge networks in science, technology and research;\n* adopt innovation as a key stimulus for investment opportunities;\n* translate the results of research into commercial ventures; and \n* contribute to excellence in training and skills acquisition.\n\nThe Higher Council for Science and Technology has identified five domains in which projects are to be implemented to operationalize the policy: the institutional framework; policies and legislation; science, technology and innovation infrastructure; human resources; and the science, technology and innovation environment. An analysis of the national innovation system revealed that research was making an insufficient contribution to economic growth and to solving chronic problems, such as those related to water, energy and food. For the 2013\u20132017 period, some 24 projects were proposed at a projected cost of around US$14 million that was yet to be allocated by the government as of 2015. These include a review of the national policy for science and technology, institutionalizing innovation, developing incentive schemes for researchers and innovators, founding technology incubators and setting up a research database. A unit is to be created within the Higher Council for Science and Technology specifically for expatriate Jordanian scientists. The council is responsible for implementing, following up and evaluating all 24 projects, along with relevant ministries.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Observatory of Science, Technology and Innovation ===\nSince about 2009, the Higher Council for Science and Technology has been involved in a project that is setting up an Observatory of Science, Technology and Innovation, in collaboration with the United Nations\u2019 Economic and Social Commission for Western Asia (ESCWA). The observatory will maintain the country's first comprehensive database of domestic research and is to be hosted by the Higher Council for Science and Technology.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== National Innovation Strategy ===\nIn 2013, the Higher Council for Science and Technology published the ''National Innovation Strategy, 2013\u20132017'' (despite the similarity in name, not to be confused with the ''Science, Technology and Innovation Policy and Strategy,'' 2013\u20132017). The ''National Innovation Strategy, 2013\u20132017'' had been prepared in collaboration with the Ministry of Planning and International Co-operation, with the support of the [[World Bank]]. Targeted fields include energy, environment, health, ICTs, nanotechnology, education, engineering services, banking and clean technologies.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Scientific Research Support Fund ===\nJordan's Scientific Research Support Fund was revived in 2010 after being instituted in 2006. Administered by the Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research, it finances investment in human resources and infrastructure through competitive research grants related to ecological water management and technological applications. The fund backs entrepreneurial ventures and helps Jordanian companies to solve technical problems; it also encourages private bodies to allocate resources for R&D and provides university students with scholarships based on merit. So far, the fund has provided 13 million Jordanian dinars (''circa'' US$18.3 million) to finance R&D projects in Jordan, 70% of which has been used to fund projects in energy, water and health care.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Fund for Scientific Research and Vocational Training ===\nThe revamped Scientific Research Support Fund is also intended to streamline the activities supported by the Fund for Scientific Research and Vocational Training (est. 1997). This fund was launched partly to ensure that all public shareholding Jordanian companies either spent 1% of their net profits on research or vocational training within their own structure or paid an equivalent amount into the fund for redistribution for the same purpose. The problem was that the definition of what constituted research and vocational training was too broad. As a result, new regulations were adopted in 2010 to clarify the terms and provide for the collection of the 1% to be spent on research and development.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Higher education ==\n\n=== Policy issues ===\nEgypt, Iraq, Jordan, Lebanon, Palestine, Sudan and Syria all boast relatively mature higher education infrastructure that includes some of the oldest universities in the Arab world.<ref name=\":0\" /> Jordan's largest university, for instance, the [[University of Jordan]], was founded in 1962. It claims to have 17% international students.\n\nLike other Arab governments, Jordan is setting up an observatory to monitor its innovation system. When studying the data collected, however, analysts often see a direct correlation between the number of graduates or faculty and the number of researchers. This is misleading, as many students and faculty members do not conduct research and only a few actually publish in refereed journals listed by the Web of Science or Scopus and have international contacts. Many Arab universities are simply not research universities. Moreover, until recently, the terms of reference for a university professor in the Arab region did not include research, but now most of the universities take research into account as the main standard for that. The real test comes from counting the time spent effectively by an individual on research, as opposed to teaching or other tasks. It is rare for the actual research activity of teaching staff in government and most private universities to exceed 5\u201310% of their total academic duties, compared to 35\u201350% in European and American universities. In Jordan and many other Arab states, the bulk of scientific research is carried out within a higher education system that is faced with its own problems, including scarce resources and burgeoning student numbers. Under pressure to submit to the diktats of international university rankings, rectors are no longer certain whether their institutions should aim to generate knowledge (i.e. scientific publications) or transmit knowledge (i.e. teach).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Trends in higher education ===\nThe most recent data available for government spending on education (4.94% of GDP), including higher education (0.92% of GDP), date from 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://data.uis.unesco.org/?queryid=181|title=Government expenditure on higher education as a percentage of GDP|date=2017|website=UNESCO Institute for Statistics}}</ref> There were 60,686 tertiary students in 2011. Just 12% of them (7,225) graduated in science and engineering fields that year, compared to 44% in Tunisia.  In 2014, 52% of tertiary graduates in science, engineering and agriculture were women. They accounted for 65% of students in natural sciences, 13% of those in engineering and 74% of those studying agriculture - perhaps because of the growing importance of biotechnology in agriculture.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Research trends ==\n\n=== Financial investment in research ===\nThe research intensity of Jordan is fairly low (0.43% of GDP in [http://data.uis.unesco.org/Index.aspx?queryid=64 2008]), despite a growing number of public and private universities. Jordan trails the leading members of the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] for this indicator, namely [[Innovation in Malaysia|Malaysia]] (1.07% of GDP in 2011), Turkey (0.86% of GDP in 2011), [[Science and technology in Morocco|Morocco]] (0.73% in 2010), Egypt and Tunisia (0.68% of GDP in 2013 and 2012 respectively). Moreover, these five countries have announced their intention to raise their research intensity in coming years.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn many Arab states, the bulk of domestic research expenditure is performed by the government sector, followed by the higher education sector. The private sector assumes little or even no role in the research enterprise. Jordan, Morocco, Oman, Qatar, Tunisia and the United Arab Emirates are exceptions to the rule. The European Commission's Erawatch has estimated that the private sector performs one-third of research expenditure in Jordan. This compares with 30% in Morocco (2010), 29% in the United Arab Emirates (2011), 26% in Qatar (2012) and 24% in Oman (2011), according to Erawatch. The figure is closer to 20% in Tunisia, according to the [[UNESCO Institute for Statistics]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Human resources ===\nIn a context of rapid population growth, the number of researchers per million inhabitants is a more telling indicator of progress than sheer numbers. Jordan had 9,092 researchers (in head counts) in 2015, according to the [[UNESCO Institute for Statistics]], a density of 1,197 researchers per million inhabitants. These figures were higher in 2008, when there were 11,310 researchers in Jordan, representing a density of 1,913 per million inhabitants.[http://data.uis.unesco.org/Index.aspx?queryid=64]\n\nThe share of women researchers dropped between 2008 and 2015 from 22.5% to 19.7%.[http://data.uis.unesco.org/Index.aspx?queryid=64]  In 2008, women accounted for 26% of researchers in natural sciences, 18% of those in engineering, 44% of those in medical sciences, 19% of those in agricultural sciences and 32% of researchers in social sciences and humanities.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Table: Share of female Arab researchers (%)'''\n\n'''''Selected countries, in head counts'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Tunisia  (2008)\n|47.4\n|-\n|Egypt  (2013)\n|42.8\n|-\n|Bahrain  (2013)\n|41.2\n|-\n|Kuwait  (2013)\n|37.3\n|-\n|Iraq  (2011)\n|34.2\n|-\n|Morocco  (2011)\n|30.2\n|-\n|Oman (2011)\n|24.9\n|-\n|Palestine (2010)\n|22.6\n|-\n|Jordan  (2015)\n|19.7\n|-\n|Qatar (2012)\n|21.9\n|-\n|Saudi Arabia (2009)\n|1.4\n|}\nSource: For Jordan, UNESCO Institute for Statistics. For the other countries: ''UNESCO Science Report: towards 2030'' (2015), Figure 17.7. Note: the data on Saudi Arabia only cover one university.\n\n=== Research output ===\n\nBetween 2005 and 2014, the number of publications catalogued in Thomson Reuters' Web of Science (Science Citation Index Expanded) climbed in almost every country in the world. In Jordan, the number rose from 641 (2005) to 1,093 (2014), with the growth rate slowing after 2008 after publications crossed the 1,000 a year threshold. With 146 publications per million inhabitants in 2014, Jordan's output in terms of scientific papers is of median level in the Arab world. It is surpassed by Qatar (548 per million), Saudi Arabia (371), Tunisia (276), Lebanon (203), Kuwait (174), the United Arab Emirates (154) and Oman (151) for this indicator. Qatar and Saudi Arabia both increased their scientific output considerably between 2005 and 2014, as part of a drive to recruit highly cited researchers from around the world for their universities.\n\nTwo-thirds of articles produced by scientists in the Arab world between 2008 and 2014 were co-authored with international partners. Jordan's closest collaborators were based in the United States of America (1,153 articles), Germany (586), Saudi Arabia (490), the United Kingdom (450) and Canada (259).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Thomson Reuters selection of Highly Cited Researchers of 2014 listed only three Arab scientists whose \u2018first\u2019 affiliation is with a university in the Arab world. They were Prof. Ali H. Nayfeh (University of Jordan and Virginia Tech), Prof. [[Shaher El-Momani]] (University of Jordan and King Abdulaziz University in Saudi Arabia) and Prof. Salim Messaoudi (Algeria), a faculty member of King Fahd University of Petroleum and Minerals in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe majority of patent applications in Jordan are submitted by non-residents. This pattern is found throughout the Arab world. The number of patent applications submitted by Jordanian residents remained stable between 2010 and 2012 (''see table'').\n\n'''Table: Patent applications in Arab states, 2010\u20132012'''\n\n'''''For countries with more than 15 patent applications in 2012'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|\n| colspan=\"3\" |Patent applications by residents\n| colspan=\"3\" |Patent applications by non-residents\n| colspan=\"3\" |Total patent applications \n|-\n|\n|2010\n|2011\n|2012\n|2010\n|2011\n|2012\n|2010\n|2011\n|2012\n|-\n|Egypt \n|605\n|618\n|683\n|1 625\n|1 591\n|1 528\n|2 230\n|2 209\n|2 211\n|-\n|Morocco \n|152\n|169\n|197\n|882\n|880\n|843\n|1034\n|1 049\n|1 040\n|-\n|Saudi Arabia\n|288\n|347\n|\n|643\n|643\n|\n|931\n|990\n|\n|-\n|Algeria \n|76\n|94\n|119\n|730\n|803\n|781\n|806\n|897\n|900\n|-\n|Tunisia \n|113\n|137\n|150\n|508\n|543\n|476\n|621\n|680\n|626\n|-\n|Jordan\n|45\n|40\n|48\n|429\n|360\n|346\n|474\n|400\n|394\n|-\n|Yemen\n|20\n|7\n|36\n|55\n|37\n|49\n|75\n|44\n|85\n|-\n|Lebanon \n|\n|\n|\n|13\n|2\n|2\n|13\n|2\n|2\n|}\nSource: UNESCO Science Report: towards 2030 (2015), Table 17.5\n\n== King Abdullah II Design and Development Bureau ==\nJordan is home to the King Abdullah II Design and Development Bureau (KADDB), an independent government entity within the Jordanian Armed Forces that develops defence products and security solutions for the region. KADDB works with Jordanian universities to help students tailor their research projects to KADDB's needs.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Information and communications technology==\nJordan contributes 75% of the Arabic content on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jordantimes.com/news/local/75-online-arabic-content-originates-jordan|title=75% of online Arabic content originates in Jordan|date=|publisher=Jordan Times|accessdate=2015-09-29}}</ref> In fact, the ICT sector is the fastest-growing sector in the Jordanian economy with a 25% annual growth rate. The sector accounts for more than 84,000 jobs and contributes 12% to GDP. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-businessreport.com/article/the-arab-worlds-top-content-creator-takes-on-innovation/ |title=The Arab world\u2019s top content creator takes on innovation |publisher=The Business Report  |accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> There are 400 companies in Jordan operating across the spectrum of telecom, information technology (IT), on-line and mobile content, business outsourcing and video game development. It has been estimated that these subsections of the ICT industry will create over 18,000 jobs between 2015 and 2020.<ref>http://www.jcp-jordan.org/en/page/ict</ref><ref>https://photos.state.gov/libraries/jordan/444376/pdf/2014CCGFinal.pdf</ref> Roba al Assi, a Jordanian blogger who currently works at Bayt.com managing the sub-division, Bayt Communities, attributes much of the credit for Jordan's booming ICT sector to the open source community, citing groups and organizations like the Jordan Open Source Association, GeekFest and Amman Tech Tuesdays. 'What helps is that we are a country of human resources, as opposed to natural resources', he has said. 'In the absence of money and more lucrative industries, the Jordanian youth has spent the past decade building its passion for the \"you can do what you want attitude\" of our industry'. Al Issi adds the information technology educational structure to the list of Jordanian assets. 'Historically, most of the large web start-ups have been Jordanian in origin, like Manitoba, al-Bawaba and Jeeran,' she adds.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nJordan's ICT sector has also enjoyed the support of the monarchy. [[Queen Rania of Jordan|Queen Rania]] has touted the expansion of social media and used [[Twitter]] and [[YouTube]] to address the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsu.org/course_files/SRIpdfResources/CIMA_SocialMediaintheArabWorld_LeadinguptotheUprisingsof2011.pdf|title=Social Media in the Arab World: Leading up to the Uprisings of 2011|last=Graham|first=Joffery|date=February 3, 2011|website=NEWSY.org|publisher=The Center for International Media Assistance (CIMA)|accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Energy ==\n=== National energy strategy ===\n\nJordan imports over 95% of its energy needs, at a cost of about one-fifth of its GDP. Natural gas used to provide the bulk of Jordan's energy supply but this has changed since 2012, owing to gas supply constraints from Egypt. Jordan's electricity supply is now more than 90% reliant on heavy fuel oil and diesel. By 2015, Jordan is expected to need to generate 3,600 MWe to satisfy its energy needs, which are estimated to rise to 5000 MWe by 2020 and 8000 MWe by 2030.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nTo compound matters, Jordan has a water deficit of about 600 million cubic metres (m3) per year (1500 m3 demand, 900 m3 supply). It pumps about 60 million m3/yr of fossil subartesian water from the Disi/Saq aquifer, a rate that is set to rise to 160 million m3/yr in 2013.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nJordan's 2007 national energy strategy has envisaged taking 29% of primary energy from natural gas, 14% from oil shale, 10% from renewables and 6% from nuclear by 2020.\n\n=== Nuclear technology ===\nIn March 2017, the Jordan Atomic Energy Agency signed an agreement with Saudi Arabia's King Abdullah City for Atomic and Renewable Energy for a feasibility study on construction of two small modular reactors by 2020 near [[Qasr Amra]] for the production of electricity and desalinated water. Additionally, a small research reactor was inaugurated in December 2016, called the [[Jordan Research and Training Reactor]], located at the [[Jordan University of Science and Technology]] campus in [[Ar-Ramtha]]. Its intent is to train nuclear engineers in Jordan through the existing nuclear engineering programme.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/info/Country-Profiles/Countries-G-N/Jordan/ |title=Nuclear Power in Jordan |publisher=World-nuclear.org |date= |accessdate=2015-09-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Wind and solar energy ===\n[[File:Tafila_Wind_Farm_1.jpg|link=[[:en:File:Tafila Wind Farm 1]].jpg|left|thumb|The 117 MW [[Tafila Wind Farm]] in southern Jordan is the first and largest onshore wind farm in the Middle East.\n]]Inaugurated in December 2015, the 117 MW Tafila wind farm in Jordan is the Middle East's largest onshore wind power development to date.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.petra.gov.jo/Public_News/Nws_NewsDetails.aspx?Site_Id=1&lang=2&NewsID=285654|title=Masdar appoints IFC to oversee funding of Jordan\u2019s largest solar power project|date=18 January 2017|work=Petra News Agency|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nJordan is also investing in solar energy. The National Electric Power Company, Jordan's state electricity provider, signed a power purchase agreement in October 2016 with Masdar, Abu Dhabi's renewable energy company, for the construction of a 200 MW solar plant 10&nbsp;km outside Amman. The solar facility is being developed by Masdar's subsidiary, the Baynouna Solar Energy Company. Once connected to the national grid, the solar facility will supply the annual power needs of around 110,000 homes and displace an estimated 360,000 tonnes of carbon dioxide emissions each year. Masdar has selected International Finance Corporation (IFC), a member of the World Bank Group, to oversee the funding of what will be the largest solar power plant in Jordan.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe combined output of the Tafila wind farm and Baynouna solar project will account for nearly 18% of the 1.8 GW of renewable energy that Jordan plans to install by 2020.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==JY1 Cubesat==\nJordan will launch its first nano satellite [[Cubesat]] in February 2018, with the name of JY1; the late [[Hussein of Jordan|King Hussein]]'s amateur radio call sign. The satellite is being constructed by university students who received a two-month internship at NASA previously, through an initiative launched by the country's Crown Prince Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jordantimes.com/news/local/nasa-trained-young-jordanian-develops-team-nanosatellite-cubesat%E2%80%99|title=NASA-trained young Jordanian develops, with team, nanosatellite \u2018CubeSat\u2019|work=The Jordan Times|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== International cooperation in science and technology ==\n\n=== Arab Strategy for Science, Technology and Innovation ===\nIn March 2014, the Council of Ministers of Higher Education and Scientific Research in the Arab World endorsed the draft ''Arab Strategy for Science, Technology and Innovation'' at its 14th congress in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia. The strategy has three main thrusts: academic training in science and engineering, scientific research and regional and international scientific co-operation. One of the strategy's key objectives is to involve the private sector more in regional and interdisciplinary collaboration, in order to add economic and development value to research and make better use of available expertise. Up to now, science, technology and innovation policies in Arab states have failed to catalyse knowledge production effectively or add value to products and services because they focus on developing research without taking the business community on board. There has also been a lot of talk about re-orienting the education system towards innovation and entrepreneurship but little action.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the ''Arab Strategy for Science, Technology and Innovation,'' countries are urged to engage in greater international co-operation in 14 scientific disciplines and strategic economic sectors, including nuclear energy, space sciences and convergent technologies such as bio-informatics and nanobiotechnology. The ''Strategy'' advocates involving scientists from the diaspora and urges scientists to engage in public outreach; it also calls for greater investment in higher education and training to build a critical mass of experts and staunch brain drain. The ''Strategy'' nevertheless eludes some core issues, including the delicate question of who will foot the hefty bill of implementing the strategy.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== SESAME particle accelerator ===\nJordan hosts a world-class research facility which is also fostering scientific co-operation, the [[Synchrotron-Light for Experimental Science and Applications in the Middle East|Synchrotron-light for Experimental Science and Applications in the Middle East]] (SESAME), which was officially inaugurated on 17 May 2017 but had begun conducting experiments earlier.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.unesco.org/sesame-history|title=SESAME: a Visionary Endeavour in Science and Diplomacy|date=16 May 2017|work=UNESCO|access-date=10 June 2017}}</ref> Construction of the centre began in Allan in 2003 and was completed in 2008. The other eight members of SESAME are Bahrain, Cyprus, Egypt, Iran, Israel, Pakistan, the Palestinian Authority and Turkey. SESAME was established under the auspices of [[UNESCO]] at the turn of the century before becoming a fully independent intergovernmental organization in its own right.  The centre is also supported by the [[European Commission]] and by the [[European Organization for Nuclear Research]] (CERN).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSynchrotrons have become an indispensable tool for modern science. They work by accelerating electrons around a circular tube at high speed, during which time excess energy is given off in the form of light. The light source acts like a super X-ray machine and can be used by researchers to study everything from viruses and new drugs to novel materials and archaeological artefacts. There are about 50 such storage-ring based synchrotrons in use around the world. Although the majority are found in high-income countries, Brazil and China also have them.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Regional Centre for Renewable Energy and Energy Efficiency ===\nJordan is one of the ten founding members of the [[Regional Center for Renewable Energy and Energy Efficiency|Regional Centre for Renewable Energy and Energy Efficiency]], which was established in Cairo, Egypt, in June 2008. The centres acts as a platform for regional exchanges on policy and technical issues. It also encourages private-sector participation to promote the growth of a regional industry in renewable energy. The other eight founding partners are Algeria, Lebanon, Morocco, Libya, Palestine, Syria, Tunisia and Yemen. The centre has several development partners, including the [[European Union]], German Agency for Technical Co-operation and the [[Danish International Development Agency]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== ESCWA Technology Centre ===\nJordan has hosted the ESCWA Technology Centre since its inception in 2011. The centre's mission is \u2018to assist member countries and their public and private organizations to acquire the necessary tools and capabilities to accelerate socio-economic development.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Islamic World Academy of Sciences ===\nIn 1986, a handful of scientists persuaded the [[Organisation of the Islamic Conference]] (OIC) and others in the developing world to create the [[Islamic World Academy of Sciences (IAS)|Islamic World Academy of Sciences]], which is headquartered in Amman, Jordan This independent, apolitical, non-governmental organization receives seed funding from Jordan and raises funds for its activities from the OIC and other international bodies, including United Nations agencies. The Islamic World Academy of Sciences combines three functions:<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/unescosciencerep0000unse/page/259|title=UNESCO Science Report: Current Status of Science around the World|last=|first=|publisher=UNESCO|year=2010|isbn=978-92-3-104132-7|location=Paris|pages=[https://archive.org/details/unescosciencerep0000unse/page/259 259]}}</ref>\n* a learned society that promotes the values of modern science;\n* a funding agency to support outstanding scientists conducting imaginative and far-reaching research (a function not yet fully realized);\n* a leader of the scientific community of OIC member countries in its relations with governments, scientific societies and academies of sciences worldwide.\n\n=== International Continental Drilling Programme ===\nWithin the International Continental Drilling Programme, researchers from Jordan, Israel and the Palestinian Authority implemented a scientific project which entailed a deep-drilling expedition to the Dead Sea in 2010. The project involved six countries, in all.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Technology}}\n* [[University of Jordan]]\n\n==Sources==\n{{Free-content attribution\n\n | title = UNESCO Science Report: towards 2030\n| author = UNESCO\n| publisher = UNESCO Publishing\n| page numbers = 431-469\n| source = \n| documentURL = http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0023/002354/235406e.pdf\n| license statement URL = \n| license = CC-BY-SA IGO 3.0\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*{{Cite web|url = http://www.newsu.org/course_files/SRIpdfResources/CIMA_SocialMediaintheArabWorld_LeadinguptotheUprisingsof2011.pdf|title = Social Media in the Arab World: Leading up to the Uprisings of 2011|date = February 3, 2011|accessdate = May 3, 2018|website = NEWSU.org|publisher = The Center for International Media Assistance (CIMA)|last = Jeffrey|first = Graham}}\n*{{cite web|last1=Messieh|first1=Nancy|title=Jordan: the Middle East\u2019s Silicon Valley?|url=https://thenextweb.com/me/2011/06/07/jordan-the-middle-easts-silicon-valley/|accessdate=12 October 2015}}\n\n[[Category:Science and technology in Jordan| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{tone|date=September 2017}}\n{{one source|date=September 2017}}\n}}\n\n'''[[Science]] and [[Technology]]''' is '''[[Jordan|Jordan's]]''' fastest-growing economic sector. This growth is occurring across multiple industries, including information and communications technology (ICTs), solar and wind energy and nuclear technology.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jcp-jordan.org/en/page/ict|title=ICT|work=jcp-jordan.org}}</ref><ref>[https://photos.state.gov/libraries/jordan/444376/pdf/2014CCGFinal.pdf Doing Business in Jordan: 2014 Country Commercial Guide for U.S. Companies]</ref>\n\n== Science policy framework ==\n\n=== Science, Technology and Innovation Policy and Strategy ===\nJordan\u2019s Higher Council for Science and Technology (est. 1987) is an independent public body that acts as a national umbrella organization for scientific research. It is the Higher Council for Science and Technology which drew up the first national policy for science and technology in 1995. In 2013, it completed the national ''Science, Technology and Innovation Policy and Strategy'' (2013\u20132017), which has seven broad objectives. These are to:<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0023/002354/235406e.pdf|title=UNESCO Science Report: towards 2030|last=|first=|publisher=UNESCO|year=2015|isbn=978-92-3-100129-1|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref>\n* incite the government and the scientific community to adopt the requisite research priorities to develop a knowledge economy, as identified by the Higher Council for Science and Technology and the Scientific Research Support Fund in 2010 in ''Defining Scientific Research Priorities in Jordan for the Years 2011\u20132020'';\n* generalize a science culture in the education system;\n* harness research to development;\n* build knowledge networks in science, technology and research;\n* adopt innovation as a key stimulus for investment opportunities;\n* translate the results of research into commercial ventures; and \n* contribute to excellence in training and skills acquisition.\n\nThe Higher Council for Science and Technology has identified five domains in which projects are to be implemented to operationalize the policy: the institutional framework; policies and legislation; science, technology and innovation infrastructure; human resources; and the science, technology and innovation environment. An analysis of the national innovation system revealed that research was making an insufficient contribution to economic growth and to solving chronic problems, such as those related to water, energy and food. For the 2013\u20132017 period, some 24 projects were proposed at a projected cost of around US$14 million that was yet to be allocated by the government as of 2015. These include a review of the national policy for science and technology, institutionalizing innovation, developing incentive schemes for researchers and innovators, founding technology incubators and setting up a research database. A unit is to be created within the Higher Council for Science and Technology specifically for expatriate Jordanian scientists. The council is responsible for implementing, following up and evaluating all 24 projects, along with relevant ministries.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Observatory of Science, Technology and Innovation ===\nSince about 2009, the Higher Council for Science and Technology has been involved in a project that is setting up an Observatory of Science, Technology and Innovation, in collaboration with the United Nations\u2019 Economic and Social Commission for Western Asia (ESCWA). The observatory will maintain the country\u2019s first comprehensive database of domestic research and is to be hosted by the Higher Council for Science and Technology.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== National Innovation Strategy ===\nIn 2013, the Higher Council for Science and Technology published the ''National Innovation Strategy, 2013\u20132017'' (despite the similarity in name, not to be confused with the ''Science, Technology and Innovation Policy and Strategy,'' 2013\u20132017). The ''National Innovation Strategy, 2013\u20132017'' had been prepared in collaboration with the Ministry of Planning and International Co-operation, with the support of the [[World Bank]]. Targeted fields include energy, environment, health, ICTs, nanotechnology, education, engineering services, banking and clean technologies.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Scientific Research Support Fund ===\nJordan\u2019s Scientific Research Support Fund was revived in 2010 after being instituted in 2006. Administered by the Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research, it finances investment in human resources and infrastructure through competitive research grants related to ecological water management and technological applications. The fund backs entrepreneurial ventures and helps Jordanian companies to solve technical problems; it also encourages private bodies to allocate resources for R&D and provides university students with scholarships based on merit. So far, the fund has provided 13 million Jordanian dinars (''circa'' US$18.3 million) to finance R&D projects in Jordan, 70% of which has been used to fund projects in energy, water and health care.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Fund for Scientific Research and Vocational Training ===\nThe revamped Scientific Research Support Fund is also intended to streamline the activities supported by the Fund for Scientific Research and Vocational Training (est. 1997). This fund was launched partly to ensure that all public shareholding Jordanian companies either spent 1% of their net profits on research or vocational training within their own structure or paid an equivalent amount into the fund for redistribution for the same purpose. The problem was that the definition of what constituted research and vocational training was too broad. As a result, new regulations were adopted in 2010 to clarify the terms and provide for the collection of the 1% to be spent on research and development.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Higher education ==\n\n=== Policy issues ===\nEgypt, Iraq, Jordan, Lebanon, Palestine, Sudan and Syria all boast relatively mature higher education infrastructure that includes some of the oldest universities in the Arab world.<ref name=\":0\" /> Jordan's largest university, for instance, the [[University of Jordan]], was founded in 1962. It claims to have 17% international students.\n\nLike other Arab governments, Jordan is setting up an observatory to monitor its innovation system. When studying the data collected, however, analysts often see a direct correlation between the number of graduates or faculty and the number of researchers. This is misleading, as many students and faculty members do not conduct research and only a few actually publish in refereed journals listed by the Web of Science or Scopus and have international contacts. Many Arab universities are simply not research universities. Moreover, until recently, the terms of reference for a university professor in the Arab region did not include research, but now most of the universities take research into account as the main standard for that. The real test comes from counting the time spent effectively by an individual on research, as opposed to teaching or other tasks. It is rare for the actual research activity of teaching staff in government and most private universities to exceed 5\u201310% of their total academic duties, compared to 35\u201350% in European and American universities. In Jordan and many other Arab states, the bulk of scientific research is carried out within a higher education system that is faced with its own problems, including scarce resources and burgeoning student numbers. Under pressure to submit to the diktats of international university rankings, rectors are no longer certain whether their institutions should aim to generate knowledge (i.e. scientific publications) or transmit knowledge (i.e. teach).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Trends in higher education ===\nThe most recent data available for government spending on education (4.94% of GDP), including higher education (0.92% of GDP), date from 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://data.uis.unesco.org/?queryid=181|title=Government expenditure on higher education as a percentage of GDP|date=2017|website=UNESCO Institute for Statistics}}</ref> There were 60,686 tertiary students in 2011. Just 12% of them (7,225) graduated in science and engineering fields that year, compared to 44% in Tunisia.  In 2014, 52% of tertiary graduates in science, engineering and agriculture were women. They accounted for 65% of students in natural sciences, 13% of those in engineering and 74% of those studying agriculture - perhaps because of the growing importance of biotechnology in agriculture.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Research trends ==\n\n=== Financial investment in research ===\nThe research intensity of Jordan is fairly low (0.43% of GDP in [http://data.uis.unesco.org/Index.aspx?queryid=64 2008]), despite a growing number of public and private universities. Jordan trails the leading members of the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] for this indicator, namely [[Innovation in Malaysia|Malaysia]] (1.07% of GDP in 2011), Turkey (0.86% of GDP in 2011), [[Science and technology in Morocco|Morocco]] (0.73% in 2010), Egypt and Tunisia (0.68% of GDP in 2013 and 2012 respectively). Moreover, these five countries have announced their intention to raise their research intensity in coming years.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn many Arab states, the bulk of domestic research expenditure is performed by the government sector, followed by the higher education sector. The private sector assumes little or even no role in the research enterprise. Jordan, Morocco, Oman, Qatar, Tunisia and the United Arab Emirates are exceptions to the rule. The European Commission's Erawatch has estimated that the private sector performs one-third of research expenditure in Jordan. This compares with 30% in Morocco (2010), 29% in the United Arab Emirates (2011), 26% in Qatar (2012) and 24% in Oman (2011), according to Erawatch. The figure is closer to 20% in Tunisia, according to the [[UNESCO Institute for Statistics]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Human resources ===\nIn a context of rapid population growth, the number of researchers per million inhabitants is a more telling indicator of progress than sheer numbers. Jordan had 9,092 researchers (in head counts) in 2015, according to the [[UNESCO Institute for Statistics]], a density of 1,197 researchers per million inhabitants. These figures were higher in 2008, when there were 11,310 researchers in Jordan, representing a density of 1,913 per million inhabitants.[http://data.uis.unesco.org/Index.aspx?queryid=64]\n\nThe share of women researchers dropped between 2008 and 2015 from 22.5% to 19.7%.[http://data.uis.unesco.org/Index.aspx?queryid=64]  In 2008, women accounted for 26% of researchers in natural sciences, 18% of those in engineering, 44% of those in medical sciences, 19% of those in agricultural sciences and 32% of researchers in social sciences and humanities.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Table: Share of female Arab researchers (%)'''\n\n'''''Selected countries, in head counts'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Tunisia  (2008)\n|47.4\n|-\n|Egypt  (2013)\n|42.8\n|-\n|Bahrain  (2013)\n|41.2\n|-\n|Kuwait  (2013)\n|37.3\n|-\n|Iraq  (2011)\n|34.2\n|-\n|Morocco  (2011)\n|30.2\n|-\n|Oman (2011)\n|24.9\n|-\n|Palestine (2010)\n|22.6\n|-\n|Jordan  (2015)\n|19.7\n|-\n|Qatar (2012)\n|21.9\n|-\n|Saudi Arabia (2009)\n|1.4\n|}\nSource: For Jordan, UNESCO Institute for Statistics. For the other countries: ''UNESCO Science Report: towards 2030'' (2015), Figure 17.7. Note: the data on Saudi Arabia only cover one university.\n\n=== Research output ===\n\nBetween 2005 and 2014, the number of publications catalogued in Thomson Reuters' Web of Science (Science Citation Index Expanded) climbed in almost every country in the world. In Jordan, the number rose from 641 (2005) to 1,093 (2014), with the growth rate slowing after 2008 after publications crossed the 1,000 a year threshold. With 146 publications per million inhabitants in 2014, Jordan's output in terms of scientific papers is of median level in the Arab world. It is surpassed by Qatar (548 per million), Saudi Arabia (371), Tunisia (276), Lebanon (203), Kuwait (174), the United Arab Emirates (154) and Oman (151) for this indicator. Qatar and Saudi Arabia both increased their scientific output considerably between 2005 and 2014, as part of a drive to recruit highly cited researchers from around the world for their universities.\n\nTwo-thirds of articles produced by scientists in the Arab world between 2008 and 2014 were co-authored with international partners. Jordan's closest collaborators were based in the United States of America (1,153 articles), Germany (586), Saudi Arabia (490), the United Kingdom (450) and Canada (259).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Thomson Reuters selection of Highly Cited Researchers of 2014 listed only three Arab scientists whose \u2018first\u2019 affiliation is with a university in the Arab world. They were Prof. Ali H. Nayfeh (University of Jordan and Virginia Tech), Prof. [[Shaher El-Momani]] (University of Jordan and King Abdulaziz University in Saudi Arabia) and Prof. Salim Messaoudi (Algeria), a faculty member of King Fahd University of Petroleum and Minerals in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe majority of patent applications in Jordan are submitted by non-residents. This pattern is found throughout the Arab world. The number of patent applications submitted by Jordanian residents remained stable between 2010 and 2012 (''see table'').\n\n'''Table: Patent applications in Arab states, 2010\u20132012'''\n\n'''''For countries with more than 15 patent applications in 2012'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|\n| colspan=\"3\" |Patent applications by residents\n| colspan=\"3\" |Patent applications by non-residents\n| colspan=\"3\" |Total patent applications \n|-\n|\n|2010\n|2011\n|2012\n|2010\n|2011\n|2012\n|2010\n|2011\n|2012\n|-\n|Egypt \n|605\n|618\n|683\n|1 625\n|1 591\n|1 528\n|2 230\n|2 209\n|2 211\n|-\n|Morocco \n|152\n|169\n|197\n|882\n|880\n|843\n|1034\n|1 049\n|1 040\n|-\n|Saudi Arabia\n|288\n|347\n|\n|643\n|643\n|\n|931\n|990\n|\n|-\n|Algeria \n|76\n|94\n|119\n|730\n|803\n|781\n|806\n|897\n|900\n|-\n|Tunisia \n|113\n|137\n|150\n|508\n|543\n|476\n|621\n|680\n|626\n|-\n|Jordan\n|45\n|40\n|48\n|429\n|360\n|346\n|474\n|400\n|394\n|-\n|Yemen\n|20\n|7\n|36\n|55\n|37\n|49\n|75\n|44\n|85\n|-\n|Lebanon \n|\n|\n|\n|13\n|2\n|2\n|13\n|2\n|2\n|}\nSource: UNESCO Science Report: towards 2030 (2015), Table 17.5\n\n== King Abdullah II Design and Development Bureau ==\nJordan is home to the King Abdullah II Design and Development Bureau (KADDB), an independent government entity within the Jordanian Armed Forces that develops defence products and security solutions for the region. KADDB works with Jordanian universities to help students tailor their research projects to KADDB\u2019s needs.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Information and communications technology==\nJordan contributes 75% of the Arabic content on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jordantimes.com/news/local/75-online-arabic-content-originates-jordan|title=75% of online Arabic content originates in Jordan|date=|publisher=Jordan Times|accessdate=2015-09-29}}</ref> In fact, the ICT sector is the fastest-growing sector in the Jordanian economy with a 25% annual growth rate. The sector accounts for more than 84,000 jobs and contributes 12% to GDP. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-businessreport.com/article/the-arab-worlds-top-content-creator-takes-on-innovation/ |title=The Arab world\u2019s top content creator takes on innovation |publisher=The Business Report  |accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> There are 400 companies in Jordan operating across the spectrum of telecom, information technology (IT), on-line and mobile content, business outsourcing and video game development. It has been estimated that these subsections of the ICT industry will create over 18,000 jobs between 2015 and 2020.<ref>http://www.jcp-jordan.org/en/page/ict</ref><ref>https://photos.state.gov/libraries/jordan/444376/pdf/2014CCGFinal.pdf</ref> Roba al Assi, a Jordanian blogger who currently works at Bayt.com managing the sub-division, Bayt Communities, attributes much of the credit for Jordan's booming ICT sector to the open source community, citing groups and organizations like the Jordan Open Source Association, GeekFest and Amman Tech Tuesdays. 'What helps is that we are a country of human resources, as opposed to natural resources', he has said. 'In the absence of money and more lucrative industries, the Jordanian youth has spent the past decade building its passion for the \"you can do what you want attitude\" of our industry'. Al Issi adds the information technology educational structure to the list of Jordanian assets. 'Historically, most of the large web start-ups have been Jordanian in origin, like Manitoba, al-Bawaba and Jeeran,' she adds.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nJordan's ICT sector has also enjoyed the support of the monarchy. [[Queen Rania of Jordan|Queen Rania]] has touted the expansion of social media and used [[Twitter]] and [[YouTube]] to address the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsu.org/course_files/SRIpdfResources/CIMA_SocialMediaintheArabWorld_LeadinguptotheUprisingsof2011.pdf|title=Social Media in the Arab World: Leading up to the Uprisings of 2011|last=Graham|first=Joffery|date=February 3, 2011|website=NEWSY.org|publisher=The Center for International Media Assistance (CIMA)|accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Energy ==\n=== National energy strategy ===\n\nJordan imports over 95% of its energy needs, at a cost of about one-fifth of its GDP. Natural gas used to provide the bulk of Jordan's energy supply but this has changed since 2012, owing to gas supply constraints from Egypt. Jordan's electricity supply is now more than 90% reliant on heavy fuel oil and diesel. By 2015, Jordan is expected to need to generate 3,600 MWe to satisfy its energy needs, which are estimated to rise to 5000 MWe by 2020 and 8000 MWe by 2030.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nTo compound matters, Jordan has a water deficit of about 600 million cubic metres (m3) per year (1500 m3 demand, 900 m3 supply). It pumps about 60 million m3/yr of fossil subartesian water from the Disi/Saq aquifer, a rate that is set to rise to 160 million m3/yr in 2013.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nJordan's 2007 national energy strategy has envisaged taking 29% of primary energy from natural gas, 14% from oil shale, 10% from renewables and 6% from nuclear by 2020.\n\n=== Nuclear technology ===\nIn March 2017, the Jordan Atomic Energy Agency signed an agreement with Saudi Arabia\u2019s King Abdullah City for Atomic and Renewable Energy for a feasibility study on construction of two small modular reactors by 2020 near [[Qasr Amra]] for the production of electricity and desalinated water. Additionally, a small research reactor was inaugurated in December 2016, called the [[Jordan Research and Training Reactor]], located at the [[Jordan University of Science and Technology]] campus in [[Ar-Ramtha]]. Its intent is to train nuclear engineers in Jordan through the existing nuclear engineering programme.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/info/Country-Profiles/Countries-G-N/Jordan/ |title=Nuclear Power in Jordan |publisher=World-nuclear.org |date= |accessdate=2015-09-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Wind and solar energy ===\n[[File:Tafila_Wind_Farm_1.jpg|link=[[:en:File:Tafila Wind Farm 1]].jpg|left|thumb|The 117 MW [[Tafila Wind Farm]] in southern Jordan is the first and largest onshore wind farm in the Middle East.\n]]Inaugurated in December 2015, the 117 MW Tafila wind farm in Jordan is the Middle East\u2019s largest onshore wind power development to date.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.petra.gov.jo/Public_News/Nws_NewsDetails.aspx?Site_Id=1&lang=2&NewsID=285654|title=Masdar appoints IFC to oversee funding of Jordan\u2019s largest solar power project|date=18 January 2017|work=Petra News Agency|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nJordan is also investing in solar energy. The National Electric Power Company, Jordan\u2019s state electricity provider, signed a power purchase agreement in October 2016 with Masdar, Abu Dhabi\u2019s renewable energy company, for the construction of a 200 MW solar plant 10&nbsp;km outside Amman. The solar facility is being developed by Masdar's subsidiary, the Baynouna Solar Energy Company. Once connected to the national grid, the solar facility will supply the annual power needs of around 110,000 homes and displace an estimated 360,000 tonnes of carbon dioxide emissions each year. Masdar has selected International Finance Corporation (IFC), a member of the World Bank Group, to oversee the funding of what will be the largest solar power plant in Jordan.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe combined output of the Tafila wind farm and Baynouna solar project will account for nearly 18% of the 1.8 GW of renewable energy that Jordan plans to install by 2020.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==JY1 Cubesat==\nJordan will launch its first nano satellite [[Cubesat]] in February 2018, with the name of JY1; the late [[Hussein of Jordan|King Hussein]]'s amateur radio call sign. The satellite is being constructed by university students who received a two-month internship at NASA previously, through an initiative launched by the country's Crown Prince Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jordantimes.com/news/local/nasa-trained-young-jordanian-develops-team-nanosatellite-cubesat%E2%80%99|title=NASA-trained young Jordanian develops, with team, nanosatellite \u2018CubeSat\u2019|work=The Jordan Times|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== International cooperation in science and technology ==\n\n=== Arab Strategy for Science, Technology and Innovation ===\nIn March 2014, the Council of Ministers of Higher Education and Scientific Research in the Arab World endorsed the draft ''Arab Strategy for Science, Technology and Innovation'' at its 14th congress in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia. The strategy has three main thrusts: academic training in science and engineering, scientific research and regional and international scientific co-operation. One of the strategy\u2019s key objectives is to involve the private sector more in regional and interdisciplinary collaboration, in order to add economic and development value to research and make better use of available expertise. Up to now, science, technology and innovation policies in Arab states have failed to catalyse knowledge production effectively or add value to products and services because they focus on developing research without taking the business community on board. There has also been a lot of talk about re-orienting the education system towards innovation and entrepreneurship but little action.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the ''Arab Strategy for Science, Technology and Innovation,'' countries are urged to engage in greater international co-operation in 14 scientific disciplines and strategic economic sectors, including nuclear energy, space sciences and convergent technologies such as bio-informatics and nanobiotechnology. The ''Strategy'' advocates involving scientists from the diaspora and urges scientists to engage in public outreach; it also calls for greater investment in higher education and training to build a critical mass of experts and staunch brain drain. The ''Strategy'' nevertheless eludes some core issues, including the delicate question of who will foot the hefty bill of implementing the strategy.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== SESAME particle accelerator ===\nJordan hosts a world-class research facility which is also fostering scientific co-operation, the [[Synchrotron-Light for Experimental Science and Applications in the Middle East|Synchrotron-light for Experimental Science and Applications in the Middle East]] (SESAME), which was officially inaugurated on 17 May 2017 but had begun conducting experiments earlier.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.unesco.org/sesame-history|title=SESAME: a Visionary Endeavour in Science and Diplomacy|date=16 May 2017|work=UNESCO|access-date=10 June 2017}}</ref> Construction of the centre began in Allan in 2003 and was completed in 2008. The other eight members of SESAME are Bahrain, Cyprus, Egypt, Iran, Israel, Pakistan, the Palestinian Authority and Turkey. SESAME was established under the auspices of [[UNESCO]] at the turn of the century before becoming a fully independent intergovernmental organization in its own right.  The centre is also supported by the [[European Commission]] and by the [[European Organization for Nuclear Research]] (CERN).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSynchrotrons have become an indispensable tool for modern science. They work by accelerating electrons around a circular tube at high speed, during which time excess energy is given off in the form of light. The light source acts like a super X-ray machine and can be used by researchers to study everything from viruses and new drugs to novel materials and archaeological artefacts. There are about 50 such storage-ring based synchrotrons in use around the world. Although the majority are found in high-income countries, Brazil and China also have them.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Regional Centre for Renewable Energy and Energy Efficiency ===\nJordan is one of the ten founding members of the [[Regional Center for Renewable Energy and Energy Efficiency|Regional Centre for Renewable Energy and Energy Efficiency]], which was established in Cairo, Egypt, in June 2008. The centres acts as a platform for regional exchanges on policy and technical issues. It also encourages private-sector participation to promote the growth of a regional industry in renewable energy. The other eight founding partners are Algeria, Lebanon, Morocco, Libya, Palestine, Syria, Tunisia and Yemen. The centre has several development partners, including the [[European Union]], German Agency for Technical Co-operation and the [[Danish International Development Agency]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== ESCWA Technology Centre ===\nJordan has hosted the ESCWA Technology Centre since its inception in 2011. The centre\u2019s mission is \u2018to assist member countries and their public and private organizations to acquire the necessary tools and capabilities to accelerate socio-economic development.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Islamic World Academy of Sciences ===\nIn 1986, a handful of scientists persuaded the [[Organisation of the Islamic Conference]] (OIC) and others in the developing world to create the [[Islamic World Academy of Sciences (IAS)|Islamic World Academy of Sciences]], which is headquartered in Amman, Jordan This independent, apolitical, non-governmental organization receives seed funding from Jordan and raises funds for its activities from the OIC and other international bodies, including United Nations agencies. The Islamic World Academy of Sciences combines three functions:<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/unescosciencerep0000unse/page/259|title=UNESCO Science Report: Current Status of Science around the World|last=|first=|publisher=UNESCO|year=2010|isbn=978-92-3-104132-7|location=Paris|pages=[https://archive.org/details/unescosciencerep0000unse/page/259 259]}}</ref>\n* a learned society that promotes the values of modern science;\n* a funding agency to support outstanding scientists conducting imaginative and far-reaching research (a function not yet fully realized);\n* a leader of the scientific community of OIC member countries in its relations with governments, scientific societies and academies of sciences worldwide.\n\n=== International Continental Drilling Programme ===\nWithin the International Continental Drilling Programme, researchers from Jordan, Israel and the Palestinian Authority implemented a scientific project which entailed a deep-drilling expedition to the Dead Sea in 2010. The project involved six countries, in all.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Technology}}\n* [[University of Jordan]]\n\n==Sources==\n{{Free-content attribution\n\n | title = UNESCO Science Report: towards 2030\n| author = UNESCO\n| publisher = UNESCO Publishing\n| page numbers = 431-469\n| source = \n| documentURL = http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0023/002354/235406e.pdf\n| license statement URL = \n| license = CC-BY-SA IGO 3.0\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*{{Cite web|url = http://www.newsu.org/course_files/SRIpdfResources/CIMA_SocialMediaintheArabWorld_LeadinguptotheUprisingsof2011.pdf|title = Social Media in the Arab World: Leading up to the Uprisings of 2011|date = February 3, 2011|accessdate = May 3, 2018|website = NEWSU.org|publisher = The Center for International Media Assistance (CIMA)|last = Jeffrey|first = Graham}}\n*{{cite web|last1=Messieh|first1=Nancy|title=Jordan: the Middle East\u2019s Silicon Valley?|url=https://thenextweb.com/me/2011/06/07/jordan-the-middle-easts-silicon-valley/|accessdate=12 October 2015}}\n\n[[Category:Science and technology in Jordan| ]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (10)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science_and_technology_in_Jordan"}
{"title_page": "Ethiopian Canadians", "text_new": "{{See also|Habesha peoples}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group = Ethiopian Canadians<br/>\u12e8\u12a2\u1275\u12ee\u1335\u12eb \u12ab\u1293\u12f3\u12cd\u12eb\u1295\n|population = '''44,065''' <small>[[2016 Canadian Census]]</small>><ref>{{cite web |title=Ethnic origin population |url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Ethnic%20origin&TABID=1&type=0 |website=www12.statcan.gc.ca |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=18 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"2016pop\">{{cite web |title=Ethnic origin population |url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Ethnic%20origin&TABID=1&type=0 |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=18 September 2019}}</ref><!-- per [[WP:Infobox ethnic group]], population parameter is for population & image parameter is for image/flag -->\n|popplace = [[Ottawa]], [[Toronto]]\n|langs = [[Amharic]]{{\u00b7}}[[Harari language|Harari]]{{\u00b7}}[[Oromo language|Oromo]]{{\u00b7}}[[Tigrinya language|Tigrinya]]{{\u00b7}}[[Canadian English]]{{\u00b7}}[[Canadian French]]\n|rels = [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church|Ethiopian Orthodox Christian]]{{\u00b7}}[[Islam in Ethiopia|Muslim]]{{\u00b7}}[[Beta Israel|Jewish]]\n}}\n'''Ethiopian Canadians''' are [[Canadians|Canadian citizens]] of [[People of Ethiopia|Ethiopian]] descent or an [[Ethiopia]]-born person who resides in [[Canada]]. According to the 2016 Canadian Census, 44,065 people reported Ethiopian ancestry. In addition, a number of people reported other Ethiopian ethnicity: 1,530 people had [[Amhara people|Amhara]] ancestry, 660 had [[Harari people|Harari]] ancestry, 3,350 had [[Oromo people|Oromo]] ancestry. A further 2,155 reported [[Tigrayan|Tigrian]] ancestry, although some of these might be [[Demographics of Eritrea|Eritrea]]n. <ref name=\"2016pop\"></ref> These numbers cannot be added to people reporting Ethiopian ancestry as this may lead to double counting. Of the people reporting Ethiopian ancestry, 32,790 were Canadian residents born in [[Ethiopia]] and 7,510 were recent immigrants.<ref name=\"2016im\">{{cite web |title=Immigration and citizenship |url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Immigration%20and%20citizenship&TABID=1&type=0 |website=www12.statcan.gc.ca |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=18 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable individuals==\n*[[The Weeknd]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|Africa}}\n*[[Demographics of Ethiopia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{People of Canada}}\n{{Ethiopian diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Canada]]\n[[Category:Ethiopian diaspora by country|Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ethiopian descent| ]]\n[[Category:Ethiopian Canadian| ]]\n[[Category:Ethiopian emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:African Canadian]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|Habesha peoples}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group = Ethiopian Canadians<br/>\u12e8\u12a2\u1275\u12ee\u1335\u12eb \u12ab\u1293\u12f3\u12cd\u12eb\u1295\n|population = '''44,065''' <small>[[2016 Canadian Census]]</small>><ref>{{cite web |title=Ethnic origin population |url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Ethnic%20origin&TABID=1&type=0 |website=www12.statcan.gc.ca |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=18 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"2016pop\">{{cite web |title=Ethnic origin population |url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Ethnic%20origin&TABID=1&type=0 |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=18 September 2019}}</ref><!-- per [[WP:Infobox ethnic group]], population parameter is for population & image parameter is for image/flag -->\n|popplace = [[Ottawa]], [[Toronto]]\n|langs = [[Amharic]]{{\u00b7}}[[Harari language|Harari]]{{\u00b7}}[[Oromo language|Oromo]]{{\u00b7}}[[Tigrinya language|Tigrinya]]{{\u00b7}}[[Canadian English]]{{\u00b7}}[[Canadian French]]\n|rels = [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church|Ethiopian Orthodox Christian]]{{\u00b7}}[[Islam in Ethiopia|Muslim]]{{\u00b7}}[[Beta Israel|Jewish]]\n}}\n'''Ethiopian Canadians''' are [[Canadians|Canadian citizens]] of [[People of Ethiopia|Ethiopian]] descent or an [[Ethiopia]]-born person who resides in [[Canada]]. According to the 2016 Canadian Census, 44,065 people reported Ethiopian ancestry. In addition, a number of people reported other Ethiopian ethnicity: 1,530 people had [[Amhara]] ancestry, 660 had [[Harari]] ancestry, 3,350 had [[Oromo]] ancestry. A further 2,155 reported [[Tigrayan|Tigrian]] ancestry, although some of these might be [[Eritrean]]. <ref name=\"2016pop\"></ref> These numbers cannot be added to people reporting Ethiopian ancestry as this may lead to double counting. Of the people reporting Ethiopian ancestry, 32,790 were Canadian residents born in [[Ethiopia]] and 7,510 were recent immigrants.<ref name=\"2016im\">{{cite web |title=Immigration and citizenship |url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Immigration%20and%20citizenship&TABID=1&type=0 |website=www12.statcan.gc.ca |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=18 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable individuals==\n*[[The Weeknd]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|Africa}}\n*[[Demographics of Ethiopia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{People of Canada}}\n{{Ethiopian diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Canada]]\n[[Category:Ethiopian diaspora by country|Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ethiopian descent| ]]\n[[Category:Ethiopian Canadian| ]]\n[[Category:Ethiopian emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:African Canadian]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Amhara\u2192Amhara people,Harari\u2192Harari people,Oromo\u2192Oromo people,Eritrean\u2192Demographics of Eritrea", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethiopian_Canadians"}
